re father was a Deacon in Carmarthen - the Congregational church there called the Panya, very Godly man known as Godwin Davies the Engineer. And was a solicitor of Carmarthen, with everybody, because he was a very learned man, very well read, and anybody 
w
anting advice or - would go to my grandfather for advice. Well he brought up - there were seven sisters and one brother. Lost their mother in the birth of the last sister. Well - she went from there, the - the - this uncle and aunt wanted to adopt her. Th
ey were big noises in the Baptist church, they started tra}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2100535\charrsid2636949 ining her singing, she was ever}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
 baptised there. Well - she got very tired of being regimented, you know, they were - she would have been the heiress for four or five houses they had. And - but when s
he'd go back home and see her sisters having so much freedom, made her very very homesick, and she begged of her mother to go back after five years. Then - an aunt of her - of hers, my mother's - my grandmother's sister in Baglen, they were brought in Bag
l
en, she was - she had a smallholding, cow and bees and everything else, she was taken ill, she was a housekeeper to the Yellow Jersey in Baglen. Another aunt was the - hired laundry maid of - Mrs Rupert Llewellyn, Baglen Hall, so mother went now to Auntie
 
Ann to look - she was taken ill, to look after the cow and the bees and everything else, big noise in Baglen church. And - she - the great treat was to go to Baglen - she was in Mrs Griffin Llewellyn Baglen Hall's Sunday school class, and she was taken to
 
Baglen Hall - to - the Sunday school class would all go, the great treat they'd have would be taken there to have a lovely night with Mrs Griffith Llewellyn in Baglen Hall, great honour to be - at - you know, invited there. So - she had a whale of a time 
in - in - in - and big noise with the church there of course. Went back then to Carmarthen - back to her own church there, was home, I think she - she used to go -
