Oh yes, he'd tell us stories. But - not as a - not - he wasn't - he didn't have the brill - the brilliant mind that my mother had. My father was a - what you'd call a Calvin and a puritan, all he lived for was his home, his family, and his churc
h. Now my mother was what you would call - a very broad - deeply religious person, but - a very happy witty person too, she always spread - and she loved everything - great in the world, great musicians, great operas, great singers - great writers, prolif
i
c reader, and - anything that - that was great - but - and my father was so wrapped up in his church he couldn't see anything outside that. But mother loved the great things of the world. But she'd come back and she'd say - when she'd come back to her chu
rch she'd tell my father, I know of a far greater treasurer here, my deep religious faith, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would your father ever take you out without your mother?
