 No, it was only vegetables, kidney beans he was expert and runner beans and - parsnip and carrots, all that sort of thing, it was always usual, because you know we were very fond - leeks, big thing leeks of course for - the Welsh broth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did they buy any vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
If the - if they were - if the vegetables had gone in the garden and weren't fit to eat, they - she'd buy, not very often though, that's very seldom she'd buy vegetables.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. All my brother were big fruit eaters, apples particularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about tinned fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes, she'd buy tinned fruit, and they were open on a Sunday, tinned fruit, 'cos Sunday was a big day. Some young girls were asking the other day what a boring time I must have had when
 I was young, when I was a girl. No television, no wireless - and all this sort of thing. How on earth did we spend our time? Well I tell you we didn't have time to live. I said, I'll tell you how it started on Sunday, we'd go to church at half past ten, 
service, all of us, all the family, father and mother, the lot. And people will tell you, well what did you have for dinner Mrs Davies, who's cooking your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4086906\charrsid2636949 joint}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 s? She said, do - do you - what - do you have salads? No, she said, I get dinner cook - cooked sh
e said, it'll be - everything will be on, all I've got to do now is boil my vegetables when I go back, everything will be ready, she said, and a dinner fit for the King, if you'd like to come and have some. You see. Well then we'd go there, quarter past t
w
o Sunday school, half - five o'clock we'd sing in school for the gemanva garni for the singing festival, six o'clock service, eight o'clock then - rehearsal for the great works. We had two hundred and fifty choir in our church at that time. Marvellous it 
was. It was the concert of the year, and all the big artists from London, you know, were there, the orchestra, everything, it was - it was the event of the year, considered the Dyffryn choral society - we'd - perform the Messiah, Elijah, Brahms, \{
ILLEGIBLE\}, Rossini, \{ILLEGIBLE\}, Marks and all that, well then Sunday night after - after the service at eight would be the rehearsal for those great works you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would that be once a year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Once a year. It was in April. April. Always in April. And - th
en on Monday night would be prayer meeting you see. Tuesday night would be Band of Hope and games. Wednesday night would be church meeting. Thursday night would be rehearsal again for the great works, see. And Friday night they had - my brother-in-law, Wi
l
lie Whitelam's father used to take young people in special prayer meeting. Then we'd go up perhaps to - we'd either go down to Gross, if there were rehearsals of the bymanfa, if it was time for that, or we'd go to Goitra to a service on Saturday night. We
l
l we'd no time to breathe, we were so occupied in our church. But mind we belonged to other societies - I was very fond of Welsh drama work, with a couple of drama societies, I took the lead for years in our Welsh plays. My younger sister then she was - a
 
very fine singer, she followed my mother, my mother was a very fine singer. And - when - in my mother's time they used to have bags - there was a prize for the bag, you know, in the eisteddfod, you know for the best - the prettiest bag you see, the best b
a
g, and then whoever'd win, say it was a solo or a duet or a quarter or choir - the conductor would either - but if it was a soloist the bag was put round their neck and the prize money in the bag. And Moywen has got all my mother's bags now, and there's a
 - he's got a Welsh dresser and he's got the bags all - he's very very taken up with - the old things you know, and that's what they used to do. So - oh but this concert was the concert of the year, we used to have wonderful artists. I'll never forget -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember who you used to have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes, I never forget the performance of Elijah, to me that was - one of the most dramatic performances and strangely enough Idris said they bought the records this Christmas. But he said it's not nearly as dram
atic as that performance we had in Dyffryn. Teenagers we were you see. Teenagers, before the war. Wonderful. Anybody would sing in like the - well you know, that was an experience, I'm very proud I've learnt those great works, because I - I wonder because
 
I'm left alone from a big family kept entirely alone, I remember her singing one chorus from Saint Paul, and singing with gusto all of us you know, how deep and unerring is he in his judgement. His ways are past our understanding. And any time I - I've as
k
ed - why am I kept, you see. Well of course, his ways are past our understanding. We won't realize that yet. But how true, those words - then we were just singing for the - the joy of singing, but now it's the words have become an experience now, and I'm 
v
ery proud that we've learnt those great works as something which you can dwell on, well this performance of Elijah, it was Lewis James, he was the Gerant Evans of his day, he was from Pontycma, but a great operatic star like Gerant Evans is today. But he 
l
iked his whisky. And - I can remember - you know Elsie Morton, you know who Elsie Mortan was you know you'd only got to look at Elsie's face to see what she's singing about, the expression tells you whether it's joy or sorrow or - something with a bit of 
g
usto you see, and we were singing these bahl choruses you know in the Elijah now, where Elijah had done into the - into the wilderness despondent, they'd gone to worship this - these god bahl, and they turned their god from Lord God - their faces from Lor
d
 God Jehovah and he went and you remember that lovely solo - it is enough oh Lord, now take away my life. But God - after forty days in the wilderness God gave him new strength and faith to go back to try and get the people back to worship Lord God and th
e
re's a wonderful solo in it. Well anyway, he came back to us and we had these Bahl choruses. And - and - and then there'd be a silence you see. And so - so what did Lewis James do in this performance, he turned his back to the audience and faced the choir
.
 And I'm sure Elsie - it was Elsie Morton's fire you know, because she was defying - and he said, call him louder, for a venture he sleepeth, you know, and he - and he - he had a fashion of twisting his top lip up, in scorn, and he was red in the face you
 
see. He was defying us, we were defying him. Well do you know, it went to such a tension, that James Singleton, the conductor, had to put his baton down. And just leave it between Lewis James and us. You see? He was defying is and making fun of us and he 
i
nspired us, well - Idris was only saying the other day that was the most thrilling performance of Elijah he can ever remember. This one now is the top notch London - London Symphony - the - the London BBC choral society that they've got for the record, bu
t
 it's nothing like that performance we had there. The dramatic - drama, through that Lewis James turning to us you see, and we - he fired us and we fired him, and then he had us back to Lord God of Israel, Isaac and Jacob, and - well thanks be to God he g
ot us back to it, of course - he watching over us slumbers not nor sleeps, and then - be not - thanks be to God, he leadeth us - well, I don't think I - and he said himself, Lewis Hames - he was amazed you see, at the - the fire of the choir. And -
