\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was this just from the chapel members?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Chapel members. Just the chapel members, it was wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Once a year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Once a year. And the people of Port Talbot looked forward to that, it was an annual event you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Actually we were talking about whether you had tinned vegetables.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh yes, oh non Sunday always.. A tin - tinned fruit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about tinned vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. No tinned vegetables.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Or dried?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, no, nothing like that. Peas, yes, we - oh dried peas
. Always dried peas, and dried lentils, now my mother didn't like the - the - the -the pea - the dried peas for pea soup, they were too strong, she always bought the lentils, she said they were daintier and - softer touch. Soft - softer taste altogether.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you keep any livestock for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
My father had chickens at one time, oh I must tell you this, and - he was a very very tender hearted man, a very - couldn't be cruel to - see. So - they were going to kill a chicken for Sunday, this was in West End this}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4086906\charrsid2636949  was now, and - Robert Griffith}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949  lives next door, now he was a more daring man see, not afraid of any}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4086906\charrsid2636949 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 hing. My father went out to go and kill the chicken, and he couldn't do it you see, he was in the middle of - and he - he just halved it a
nd there was the poor old chicken running round with half its head off with its nerves all going you see. Oh - my father never killed a chicken after that. And he kept chickens in West - but we didn't have them anywhere else. No. In West End, not - we did
n't have them in Park Street or here, never took delight in chickens after that, it put him off chickens. He upset - it upset him so much. We had to buy one in future.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about pigs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Pigs? No, no, never kept pigs, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who would look after the chickens when you did have them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh my father and my mother you see. Or we children. The boys - the boys - the boys would look after the chickens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How many times a week would you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - oh practically every day my mother'd but 
some - some type of meat, either as I tell you - those - pasties, meat pies, or a - soups. She always like the best end of the neck or the breast, to make a nice stew. Oh it was always a fresh meat, always. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 She wouldn't have tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No. No. No, very - no, she never delighted, she'd buy - I'll tell you what she'd do, she always bought her meat with Watkins the butcher, they'd come round with a trap every day you see, and they'd deliver steak, always a bit - you'd have a lovely bit of 
shinbone steak for one and a penny, enough for a whole family you see. And they'd come round every day with meat, whatever my mother'd order, and she'd have the pin bone every weekend and the chicken with them you see. But - there was meat every day. And 
- oh yes, and these rice puddings as I tell you, oh it was quite a - a cooked dinner every day, even if it was soup, there was always a rice pudding to follow with prunes. Yes. Every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you have different afters on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. It was always rice pudding, they loved the rice pudding.
\par 
