 go out of her way - to get us - she always encouraged us to have hobbies then. Yes. Oh yes, she was very keen on discussion. 'Cos there was nothing she loved more than a - a - a - a law case now, a law suit, and she read it on the paper she'd say, have y
o
u read this summing up today with Judge so and so, marvellous, read it, and we wouldn't know what she was talking about, she would read the paper from beginning to end, you see, and take it in like a blotting paper, and she could retain it, that's where s
he was great, oh yes, she always encouraged us to discussion.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. I'll tell you what, now we were a - we were a - a very aw
kward squad, our family although we were so close with each other, how she put up with us I don't know, now I'd one brother, my elder brother wouldn't eat meat at all and - Idris and Dai wouldn't look at - wouldn't look at - poultry, no. Well then - on Ch
r
istmas time it always had to be beef, Dai would have the gravy of the beef but he wouldn't eat the meat. Never ate meat. And I marvel with seven of us that my mother had so much patience with the cooking. How she - many a mother would say, now, it's cooke
d
, you've got to eat it. Not - not so my mother. And - Idris then he wouldn't eat - on a Christmas she'd buy the turkey, and always a piece of beef. Well if she had - this - had the spoon on the stuffing, you know, to rise the beef, and Dai could taste it 
h
e wouldn't eat it. He said after the entire - and that's how I marvel the patience she had with us. I used to tell her, well how you did it mam with such an awkward squad we all had our likes and dislikes and you catered for us all without - losing your t
emper or losing your patience. She was wonderful like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 She'd go out of her way to make what you all liked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh definitely, yes. It's what you liked she'd make. Always make - put herself out for that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What was your parents attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh - didn't like it, my mother didn't like - she always liked to see the plate cleared, possible. But she knew how - how much to give each one you see. Some were smaller eaters than others. Idris was a great eat
er of bread and butter. He'd eat it - eat a - a stack of bread and butter and an apple for tea. He was a - real bread and butter eater he was. I never saw anybody - eating bread and butter like him. She - oh, and my grandmother who came from Camarthen, oh
 - what you cutting - who are you cutting that for Mary? For Idris. She said, you - he won't eat all that. Yes he will, she said. Just an apple and the bread and butter. He was finicky about his food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 If there was something on the table you wanted like
 the salt, could you ask someone to pass it to you or did you have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, we'd ask for it. We'd ask would somebody pass it to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. Oh yes. We'd always a second helping if we wanted it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes. We had to behave ourselves on the table, table manners, and I don't think I ever saw anybody eating a meal like my mother. In - in such a - a ladylike ma
nner. Oh she wouldn't have anything sloppy. It had to be done properly. Good manners in everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you have to sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh no slouching. All had to sit up properly. To digest your food as she said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. Weren't allowed to read at the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When she said. Because - I can remember - very - she'd been painting a bedroom upstairs, and Dai now finished his food like a little b
oy you know, and my mother wasn't there to tell him to leave the table, and - we all had to say grace before and after you see. And - diolch I Dduw am y bwyd was after food of course, thank God for my good food,, so he couldn't get my mother to hear, and 
he went to the bottom of the stairs, diolch i Dduw am y bwyd, diolch i - mam, diolch i Dduw am y bwyd. And we all had to ask to be excused, oh yes, she wouldn't let you leave the table unless you was excused.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Even if she wasn't at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No,
 no. We'd have to - we - she'd - she would - we had to tell her we were leaving the table, and thank - and thank - be thankful for our food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did all the family sit at the table for the meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh mostly. On a Sunday particularly, when we were all
 home at the same time because we'd all come round - from our church together and we'd go - all day Sunday we were all together on the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 But not in the weekday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, because were weren't home -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you always have the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, always the same places. Well - always the same places. My father and mother the head and then we'd be all around it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would your father and mother be alongside one another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Or one each end?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. Alongside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who would be next to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 In rotation then, the elder to the youngest. Yes. Always in rotation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 So the eldest would be alongside one of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That's it. Dai, Will, and so - so forth. That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And you always sat in the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Same place. Everybody. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How was the meal served? By whom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh my mother. She always - saw - and she'd tell us now - everybody get out now while I'm - while I'm - getting this dinner ready and the place - we'd have to carry it in to the table, we girls. We'd carry the dinner in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would she cook the dinner at the range in the living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 But she'd be dishing it out in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That's right, in the kitchen. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 She'd dish it out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, sh
e'd dish it all. Now she said, I want to keep my wits together, nobody disturb me while I - come in and carry it in, we weren't to - she wouldn't allow any of us to talk when she was - dishing the dinner up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would she carve the meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, everything, my father never carved. No. It was always my mother would carve the meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 So she would put it all out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 All out there. My father sit by the table wait for the - bring it in you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And they would. But we girls then would carry it in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who did you give the first plate to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh to my father always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you serve it always like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 In rotation, as each one, she'd say, Dai, Will, Idris - oh yes, oh yes. Oh yes, 
yes, each one she'd tell us. That's right. That's how she liked to keep her wits together, because - she knew who - who was who and what they liked.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 There was only Blod younger than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember now when she was a baby, you were five years older than her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh I can remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When would she sit to the table and who fed her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh, she was - by my mother she was. She was next to her mother, my father then Dai and - around like that it was. Then I was next t
o Blod. And she - and I can remember the day she was born, it was snowing. And - I was very very - shocked because I - I had been a delicate baby and - been pampered with my mother quite a lot, and - the thought of another child coming and - my mother was
 forty-two you see when she had - she felt like a pros}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid200467\charrsid2636949 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
itute, because my elder brother was twenty-two, old enough to be a father, because - and funnily enough when - when she was born it was snowing on a January day,, and - when she was born oh - my brother
s were right mad, especially my elder brother, he said - and the first day she was born he said, I'm going to make a singer of this ba - this baby. And he did. And - they used to sing duets in the eisteddfods together and they thought they were father and
 daughter, they didn't know they were brother and sister or father and daughter in eistedfodds, and there were many a time with Blodwen you know. Yes, so - I can remember it - \{BLANK\}
 It was in January and I can remember it was a Saturday morning, it was sn
owing heavily. And - there was a - a la - a lady with the midwife and my mother in the bedroom, and I wanted to get into this bedroom now, I'm peeping through a crack and I could see - I wondered why I couldn't get to my mother, for there was a lady calle
d
 Mrs Stephens from Prudrith Street, and she was in with my mother with her and she said, go down you naughty girl, go down, go down. Yes, yes. So of course I was very insulted I wasn't allowed to go in to my mother, well the next thing I heard I had a bab
y
 sister. And - it was such a cold day that - mother didn't put her in the cradle at all, she kept her in bed alongside of her, well I had to lie the other side of my mother now, and I used to push her over there, I don't want to see the old thing. Well I 
h
ad an uncle in Carmarthen who was very fond of me, and he and Aunt Elizabeth now, that's in bed I tell you bedridden ninety-six, they came down, they'd, heard my trouble and they came down and he said - there's a pretty looking object this one is without 
a
ny teeth or anything, what you - what do you want a thing like this, he said, I've brought a bonnet and a shawl to take her back home to Carmarthen. Well if he did of course I yelled my heart out. And do you know we were inseparable after that. I'd do any
t
hing for her. Blood will out you see. And I felt well, well, well, and she was the same, she'd do anything for me. We were very wrapped up in each other, Blod and I. 'Cos my mother called us the second hatch, Blod, Bryn and I, because we were the younger 
generation you see. Yes.
