\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you have any presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Always presents. Oh yes, we'd have little gifts. Every child will bring a little gift of course you see, very simple of course in those days, but it was a terrific thrill, to see the children bringing it, perhaps a little handkerchief it would be and I re
member - one of them, a little teapot full of chocolates. Or a little tea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid200467\charrsid2636949 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
set. Something - or a book. Those were the pres - gifts we used to have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And you had something special to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh dear me yes. The table was a sight you know and - she'd h
ave a trifle, also a jelly, tarts, cakes, and - always - she always had prunes. And I can remember a little boy, little Scotch boy that lived in - Ian - Ian Lavery - asking her now, will you have some blancmange or jelly? I'll have some of the \{ILLEGIBLE
\} please, and then the other brother then, Roy, what will you-have Roy? I'll have some of those black things, about the prunes. And things like that stand out in a memory, and the parties you know. Oh we used to have a whale of a time. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 So you'd have guests at the party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh - and the parents would come. Children first, then the parents were having the tea afterwards. And the children were allowed games then in the front room, they'd go from the living room to the front room. Then we play games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did you play?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh, she - there was one game which was - we - we used to have - postman's knock of course, and - forfeits. And - one game, three would sit on the settee. And - a stocking would be filled with papers or cotton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid200467\charrsid2636949 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 wool or somethi
ng like that and one of our legs would be pinned up under us, see. And this artificial - this stocking will be put under us like a real leg, and it - they - they - the person would be called in from the passage into the room, to try for game, would have t
o
 pull our legs, and the last one would be this stocking. Well when the leg would come off they'd be sacred stiff. And there were screams and I can always remember that. And my mother of course would be in charge of the games and the things she - she enjoy
e
d more to hear the fun and the rollicking, some were take it in good part, some would cry, they'd be so shocked to see this leg coming off. Always remember that game. Oh always full of game - full of fun. Musical chairs, musical chairs. And - postman's kn
ock as I say. I can't remember many more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And the parents would come to pick up the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh dear yes. They'd come and pick up the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Can you remember anything you did with your mother and father together on Christmas Day? What was Christmas Day like when you were little?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh wonderful. Oh wonderful. Yes, we had - in the morning, seven o'clock meeting what we - which we called plugy in Welsh, that meaning kneeling. It was a prayer meeting held in the vestry of our chur
ch, and that was seven o'clock in the morning. And what I can remember very well, when we'd come back from that, mother would buy - two pound of palethorpe sausage you see. And - when we'd come back - we'd all - sit down to our breakfast to have whatever 
w
e like, but we always ate this sausage cold you see. 'Cos we were up at four seeing what was in our stockings. And then - it was a very jolly day with us at home then, so much music. We'd have our friends and - and - well if we - when we started courting 
of course, our young men there. And - the elder boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You'd come home from chapel and you'd have the sausage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When would you have your Christmas dinner then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Christmas dinner, oh yes, oh that was quite a do. Oh dinner hour, dinner hour, dinner time. Then }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid200467\charrsid2636949 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949  oh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid200467\charrsid2636949  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
a big tea, tarts, trifles, everything else and - all the crowd, the house was always packed. Yes, always. On a Christmas Day. And then there was music in the front room, singing, hymns, carols and - everything else. It wa
s quite a day. And Boxing day. We had two wonderful days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did you do on Boxing Day?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh big crowds come in on Boxing Day too. It was always open door.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would they be friends in the street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. Friends in the church. Yes, friends in the church mostly, and friends living around that were very close to us, very old friends.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. One time we had three pianos there. And they were all going together, well it was pandemonium let loose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about when you were living in Park Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, we had - we had them there. We had two pianos there and that was - it was the same wherever we went. It was a house full of music.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How many of you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Everyone of us played something. We played the piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you have other instruments besides the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes. Violin, my brother, Will was very interested in violin, 'cos my husband was a very fine violinist, he was a professional, yes. Oh yes, we did. Yes.
 And a banjo I can remember my brother Will having a banjo. And I tell you the - the star turn on that was - the Welsh anthem, Gwyar gwelltyn syrth y blodeuyn, and that was his star turn on this banjo. Yes, oh we had a wonderful time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was there anyone in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes. From my mother down. My mother sang, my elder brother, who was a - the organist of our church, had a glorious tenor voice. Then - we - we all had good choral voices, but my young - younger sister - with my eldest sist - 
brother, followed my mother, she took the lead in opera for years in the town. Was a lovely little actress, was beautiful voice, a lyrical soprana, and - there was one statement I remember in the operatics society, she started at seventeen, and she - her 
f
irst part was in Iolanthe, shepherdess, Phyllis, and I can remember her - reporters would come from London to see the show and there was a - a - a paper called the Amateur Stage, which was produced in London, and I can remember being - it was sent down to
 
us - I've got the cuttings all here, my mother always cut them out, and she was so proud to see the children taking part actively, and - it said, and we had a wonderful man called Mr Teddy Morris, he was the comedian, and that's what it said in this artic
le of this leading soprano and the comedian were fit to adorn a London stage, and we were very proud of that. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you ever make music as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Yes. We used to be all round the piano, and we were like a - like a choir there. And 
- every - everyone could sing their own part you see. Yes, 'cos my elder, my elder brothers lovely tenor voice, my second brother was a baritone - the - and - Idris, my sister was a - Mrs White - Mrs Merchant - she was young, she - she would - she wasn't 
though - a keen - a choral singer as we were, she didn't join so many choirs, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When would you make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh any time. Oh, in the nights. And - particularly on a - on a Sunday, or if there was a party, or we had visitors
. We'd always join in - and - I can remember Idris was a very nice pianist, my - Idris was, when he was very young, and his star turn was the Hallelujah Chorus, if we had visitors, his star turn was - playing the Hallelujah Chorus on the piano. And of cou
r
se when he learnt the organ with my elder - with my brother when he was organist, he - he - wanted to learn the organ with him, because he was an organist. And - he gave him wonderful advice. Firstly, he said, learn all your hymns, be a good interpreter o
f
 your hymns. You are part of the service. Secondly, don't sit on a stool when you play an organ, for your own vain glory, you're there for the glory of god. Thirdly, keep your hands clean that they're fit to adorn and to play in the sactuary of God, you s
ee, that was the advice he gave my brother, and he still playing and - always complimented on interpretation, and we were that sort. Always music and singing and playing in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When there were part
ies. They weren't - they weren't - now my father was rather narrow. He was very much against cards, you see. And - we'd bring friends in and we'd have a game of whist and - no betting of course, but he was much narrower in outlook than my - than my mother
 
was. But she let us enjoy - the games. But she never joined in with us. She allowed us - and particularly sport now - all clean sport she liked us to join in. You see. And I can remember - my nephew asking her once - she was very fond of talking about the
 
old days and the church, the wonderful times we had with the great preachers years ago, and it was a very warm church, spiritually, and the old ladies would be praising when the great giants of a preacher, and I can remember this nephew - she was very fon
d
 of telling us about these old times you see, and she'd tell the grandchildren the same. And - I remember this nephew of mine - Moywen Merchant, a Professor in Exeter now, asking her when he was a student - young student, Gran - how is the preaching today
?
 Because he was interested in preaching too. Not as good as it was years ago? Oh yes, she said, it was. If the little Minister, the preacher this last Sunday night preached the sermon he preached last Sunday night, it would have been an excellent sermon, 
a
nd it would - they would have been on fire if it was preached years ago. But the - the ground is too dry you see, it's not receiving the seed. Oh, he said - 'cos there's no - nothing like the praising of years ago. No, that was a little bit of dew from he
a
ven, she said, with God we'd have a - he said, well - that was emotion you know Gran. Was it indeed she said, well, it was very wonderful emotion, were to God we'd have a bit more of it. That's a little bit of dew from heaven you see, she said. Oh he said
 
- she said, where's that emotion gone to Modwyn? Oh, he said - education has risento such heights you see. That people have learnt the wayto control themselves. Oh. Have they indeed? I'll take you up on that word control. Now, she said - you know I love t
o
 see my children playing all sorts of clean sport, football, any sort of good game that was going I always - entertained in the - in their world with them, liked a clean sport. Always liked to see them joining in. But - you see, she said, we are - we are 
t
wo parts, body and soul. We have to exercise both. If we - this was the advice she gave us as youngsters. If we eon't ex - if you exercise the body too; much you're shrivelling the soul. If you exercise the soul too much you're shrivelling the body. We - 
w
e had - as we are two parts we have to be moderate in all the - exercise the both, and I believe in that. Well now then, she said, I've never been to a football match in my life. But I'll come next Saturday out to the football field with you Modwyn. To wa
t
ch this - this - game of football to these wonderful people who are educated like yourself, preachers, ministers, schoolmasters, all types of people, she said, they tell me, in this game of football who have learnt how to control themselves because of edu
c
ation, but what are they doing, she said. Shouting their heads off over a little - a little bag full of - leather full of wind. Now, she said, don't think I'm a spoilsport and I'm not against football, but you are talking about people able to control them
selves today better than we did. But I - give me the old ladies who were praising years ago, they had something to shout about, they had life eternal. Well, he said, well done Gran, Shakespeare or Wordsworth wouldn't have given better advice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 They didn't actually play any games with you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, no, never played games. Only in the parties I say when we were children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Your father didn't like you playing cards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Cards, no. No. I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were there any books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 O
h yes. Plenty of books. All of us were - were - mother being a prolific reader of everything, she'd read a newspaper from beginning to end. She'd read - she'd tell you the football as well or the cricket as well, she was interest - but one thing she was a
gainst were - was - boxing. And she'd like to have gone to Parliament to speak with Lady Symmerskill - about - against boxing, because she was against it because it affected the brain in years to come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you have a newspaper in the house when you were children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Yes. Always had a newspaper. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes. The - I can always remember on Christmas my brother will would bring back Pears Magazine was a big thing, and a - oh beautiful coloured pictures, and it was showing 
different decorations for Christmas, which mother loved to see. And I remember it was half a crown in those days. And it was a wonderful magazine, this Pears magazine. And we'd have magazines in the week. Tit-Bits was a big thing. Because my brother would
 try the competitions, I remember once he was going to win a horse and trap, on this competition, but it didn't come off. Oh it was great fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember your mother or father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh dear yes. My mother was a prolific reader of everything. But my father, it was a - the Bible or religious works with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would he read the newspaper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes. Oh yes, he loved - and in his - in his life - as he was - the latter days he used to have to have a magnifying glass, his eyes were very -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember him reading when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. He always read the newspaper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did they ever read aloud to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 My mother did, oh she loved reading aloud. But my father never read aloud. Unless he'd read a chapter - or some
thing like that you know, from - from the Bible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would they read to each other, would your mother read to your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did she read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 The papers, any books. If there was something - she was very fond - of little sayin
gs now. Little mottos. And she's written them all out, she's bot - I've got lines of them here. She'd write - tell you one very - ken - keen motto she loved, if there was anyone in hospital she would - she was a wonderful letter writer, in Welsh or Englis
h
 and the remarkable thing that she only had primary school education was, but she could spell, she was never lost for a spelling word in Welsh or English. And - people tell me now that they've still got the letter, but this is what she'd write to somebody
 
who was in hospital. The services of the hands are as holy as lips that pray. And she'd explain it in this way. We do the praying, we leave the services of the hands to the great skill of the doctors, or the tender nursing of the nurses. Where she had tha
t from I don't know. But she always wrote that, and everybody -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 She'd write them down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - well, yes, I've got - I've got pages of them written down, anything that took her fancy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would she read aloud to you when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What would she read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Anything that she - fancied - if she'd read a book now. She was very fond of poems. And she loved Patience Strong or any - anything like that. She'd read this out. Listen to this, she'd say, here's a lovely - here's a lovely bit. Or an article.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How about when you were very young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh she'd read - books to us then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would your father read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. He'd read occasionally, but not like my mother, and she'd always read these - fairy tales, Gr
imms Fairy Tales was the big favourite with her. We had a lovely thick book of Grimms, and she'd love - and she'd a wonderful way of - putting it out you know, very descriptive. Which used to frighten us sometimes mind, 'cos she could act it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was this frightening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh very, there's lots of them very frightening, and then in the night perhaps we wouldn't sleep for fright. After these fairy tales.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What would happen then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - we'd go to sleep eventually you see after having a good weep perhaps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
I can - the first funeral I can remember - was - my grandfather. My - my grandfather in Carmarthen, this grandfather, he was a wonderful man, we looked up to him like a king and - the - I was - I m
ust have been about nine when he died, because the time King Edward the VII died, and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 1901?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That's right. Well I can remember that well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Or 1910?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 1910. Well - eleven I'd be then, I can remember that and Blodwen was younger and we w
ent to Rock Carmarthen to the - service, the memorial service in Rock Carmarthen. And - it was wonderful, I can remember we were in white. And we had white hats with black true lover's knots and ribbon, on the hats, I can remember that well, and - how all
 
my aunts were weeping with - because he'd been a father and mother to the family you see. That I can remember. And of course I can remember - when I was young - if anybody from the choir and the church would die - the whole choir would go outside the hous
e
 - and we'd sing, a hymn, you see, outside the house, and we'd walk in procession to the cemetery, with the - with the - funeral, over the graveside we'd sing again as a choir, and it was very very touching. The singing with the - with the choir. Remember
 the conductor of the choir then - dying, it was terrific - funeral that was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What was that like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
From West End. Singing outside the house and marching right through Pencarb to Holy Cross church. From Taibach to Holy Cross Church, wonderful singi
ng over the grave there, gravestone, graveyard. And - that to me was one of the most outstanding funerals I was ever in, I was very young then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Your grandfather's funeral in Carmarthen that would be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember who went to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes, yes. Well that was a memorial service on a Sunday night, but we didn't go - we didn't go to the funeral, but they used to hold a memorial - when - when a - an elder died, a man who was important in the church, they'd have a memorial s
ervice, the following Sunday night in the church, and all the families would go and I can remember that very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You don't remember a funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. But it was a very - no. Oh yes, lot's of funeral in Park Street of neighbours you know. And they
 were always walking and always carrying the body.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who would carry the body?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh men. And they'd change, they'd take the bier - as they call the bier - and carry it on their shoulders, very weight - weighty with the coffin, it was - oh - and the
y'd change every so often, this bier, they'd put it down and a - and the funeral procession would stop, well a new lot of men would put it on their shoulders and carry it. Very seldom would see as we have today a charabier. It was always carrying the body
. It was considered - very very respectful, it was a - a - a mark of respect to carry the body. With - with the - the people carrying it. Yes. It was very very -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would they have
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, but funnily enough mother never liked that, she never encourage
d that. I remember when my younger brother died at twenty-seven - and - he always told my mother, never make a display when - when he was - he was very ill before he died - never make a display of my body. And I never liked seeing anybody - passed on. I -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No. I never liked to see anybody - in a - in - in a coffin, I liked to remember them as they were. And mother never forced it. We could do as we liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 But they used to be on view didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh dea
r me, yes. Oh it was right, you never closed the coffin 'til the moment - that the funeral service was held in the house you see. There was a funeral service first, then you'd go in to Holy Cross church - there's non-conformist, didn't always go in the ch
u
rch somewhere if the vicar was - taking part, but if - if a Presbyter - non-conformist minister would take part, the service would be in the house first, sometimes if they were important in their own church the body would he taken to the church and - take
n into the church and the service there, then taken to the cemetery. But always - big singing - and always walking, very big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid132301\charrsid2636949 cort\'e8ge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949  after the - oh all walking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would women go as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, public. Public. Babies in arms and - everybody'd go t
o funerals. Now you're sort of dispatched so quickly. There's no respect today to a - to a body you know. Not as it used to be. But there was respect for everything years ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would people wear different clothes for funerals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh dear, everybody 
in black. Oh yes, they wouldn't dream of going in anything coloured. And particularly the mourners. Deep black to stockings, oh you wouldn't dream of going to a funeral or - or for a twelve month after you'd wear mourning. Always.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were you taken out visiting neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes. Yes. Very friendly people years ago. The neighbours were always friendly and I'll tell you another thing, if any of the children were taken ill, say we had the measles, something like that, the neighbours would come in an
d - the same with us in our house if any of - of - of - us now had the measles or any complaint they'd come in and say, Mrs Davies, pack up the clothes now, we'll do the washing and ironing for you. And it'd be washed and ironed. There was such a friendli
n
ess with the neighbours years ago. You were one community. Everybody was interested in each other, not as they are today, you can be dead next door and you would know nothing about it. But - years ago, we - we have lost that - sort of respect to one anoth
er and friendliness, and kindness too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you be taken out visiting friends or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you go with your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Always. Oh - oh we'd go - go the mother and father, the two would go together. But we'd alwa
ys go with the mother, especially to see relatives. And friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Well - we'd - remember Mrs Joseph Jones, now she had been very friendly with my mother, we'd go there. Every Boxing Day Esther was the same age as Blod, little g
irls, she - her birthday was on Boxing Day, and - we three younger ones were in January. I was on the thirteenth, Blod the sixteenth, Bryn on the thirtieth, and we'd go to her party on Boxing Day, and they'd come to us. We'd - we'd - go - visit - all the 
friends. Regularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes, and relations. All the relations round you know, and some relatives you were more friendly with than others, seemed to be closer to some relatives didn't you, than you would with others and - oh yes, it was quite a thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 With whom would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh with my mother and - my mother and my father if he was available, he wasn't working, but mostly with my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were you taken shopping?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Yes. And I can remember when my sis
ter started courting, Liz, she started - tell you start at sixteen, and I'd be out playing with friends you see. This was in Park Street. And - she was courting a - a - Willie Merchant who lived opposite, and - Friday night I'd be - it used to make me ver
y
 very annoyed, she'd bring me in from my play with my friends, as a little girl, and - and - wash - wash me and dress me and I was always dressed in a navy reefer coat with a red turn, always with brass buttons. And - she'd - she'd take me over as a sort 
o
f - a scapegoat then you see. And - we'd always meet her boyfriend, Willie Merchant, in the market. It was cut and dried. For I was the scapegoat and I can remember one day half way over, she found I had a hole in my stocking. And I remember her giving me
 
a few slaps because I - as if I could help. She took me from play. Because I was - so - respectably dressed and I had this hole in my stocking, that's as visit as if it was yesterday. And then they'd meet in the market and I used to get very bored, they w
ith their conversation there, sweet nothings in the market and I was standing there, you know, like a lemon listening to all this. Oh. I was the baby sister then before Blod was born. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 If you went shopping with whom would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh with my mother always. Always with may - and I'd go with this sister too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you go once a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes. Yes every week got town, with my mother once a week. Always once a week to town. But - or to Taibach. To do the shopping. So we loved that 'cos we
'd always have some sweets you see. And - it was a great treat to have a - some sweets, they were a very few pence - knocking around at that time but - we'd always have a treat to come back, and I remember when I was a little girl, Ellis' shop, they were 
t
he confectioners in Station Road, and they were experts on making - congress tarts. And - my mother would buy these congress tarts for us in Ellis' and - and chocolate drops. That I can remember very well, and in - in - in the confectioners he was a - a v
ery nice man, had been there - oh well, when the shop was first built, I've got a photograph of it now. Of the shop, with just a horse and cart in Station Road, now how different it is. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Down
 the docks as I say on Saturday, every Saturday afternoon. He'd take me down - the - Port Talbot docks was a very busy dock at that time. It exported so much coal. And brought in - fruit from Spain. There was a - a - a ship called the Dorygoch and it had 
a
 - a very strange - hooter, and we'd always know when the Dorygoch was in, it was from Spain, and it always brought a - on a load of oranges in and we'd say, oh the Dorygoch's in. It had a very very queer - hooter. But every Saturday it was full of sailin
g ships. My father would take me down to the docks to wa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid132301\charrsid2636949 tch the boat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
s coming in with the pilot boat. And the - the lock gates opening and describing the ships to me and the way they were brought in, that was the thrill of my Week, when my father take me down to the docks.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember any other outings with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes. Up to the Dyffryn Valley we'd go. Down to Aberafan beach. Families would go there, we'd have a whale of a time. With baskets full of food, and this - diodfaen as we sa
y, the small beer, and you see, with a - with a - with you walking and shaking it would ferment, you see, the balm in it, and the corks would be flying all over the place. And that would shoot out of the bottles and we'd lose half the diod - half the smal
l beer before we'd arrive at the beach. But there was always a fire lit and we'd undress before the fire and go into the sea. It was a lovely beach, very safe - at that time. And then we - another picnic we'd look forward to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How would you get down to Aberafan beach?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Not Aberafan, Taibach beach. Oh walk down over the - over the dunes, and over the - over the - what we call the blackberry patch, now the Abystwch works, it's all built all over it you see. Abbey Steel Works and the market.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you go in the water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes. Go in the water - water there. And years ago the mothers now - they weren't as posh as they are now, every - all of them wouldn't have - bathing costumes, they'd go in their nightdresses. Yes. And they would be floating
 in the sea you know, like a parachute. And - and my mother was foolish enough once to keep it on - while she was boiling the kettle, and - and the fires would be make on the beach, boiling the kettle on the fire. Sticks would be found, and lit, find old 
p
ieces of coke, perhaps some of the boats would have - lost a lot of coal on the beach, and they'd light a fire, and I can remember mother one year not taking this nightdress off, having tea - and went in again - went in again, and she developed pleurisy t
h
rough it. So she had a lesson, that she wouldn't go in in her nightdress again. Then we went up to a - have a picnic at - the Sunday school'd go up there, to Dyffryn Farm, in Dyffryn Valley and Cwmwyn Valley. Where the reservoir is. And there was a lovely
 
place to play games there. The Sunday school or the church - but in Dyffryn Park a big marquee would be put up in the Dyffryn Farm, and we'd all have a wonderful time, but I can remember one tea, it had poured with rain. And the rain was coming through th
e
 marquee and all - in all quarters, and we were soaking wet, it spoilt the tea. And the Tomases the Dyffryn Farm were big members of our church, and they'd allow us to play in the fields and we'd have a wonderful time, up in the Dyffryn Farm. And I can re
m
ember another time, mother used to by milk - we used to buy milk with a - a farm, Davis's, Cwnwena - Cwngwena Farm, you know Davis's Cwmgwena - what do you call it - James Cwngwena, and their children, well - his mother, she was Mrs Davis, and they sold m
i
lk and we bought milk with them. Well once a year she would have the families up on a gam buch - up to the farm. All the people who bought milk, and we'd have turns as families, but what was - what a treat - to be taken up on a gam buch to the farm. And I
 
can remember - my mother saying - this was just before I was born, that - we'd gone up - and Mrs Davis Cwngwena said, now children, you can go to the gardens and pick what you like, but don't pick - the gooseberries with the hairs on. You know, the - the 
-
 the - the - the eatable gooseberries of course, the - so she - and - do you know, because she said that mother was longing for one before I was born. Longing for these gooseberries. And would you believe it, I've been born with a birthmark at my side, wi
th a gooseberry and the hairs on it. Yes, really. Oh it was great fun. Oh dear.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes. We - were take - it was always down to the beach, down to - Taibach, but - mother once took us to Aberafan beach one year, and that
