s a working man, and he decided he couldn't listen to Edward Matthews or talk to him. Had heard that this great preacher voted Tory. And he said to Marga, his wife, I'm not going to listen to him or speak to him any more. And - to think of a Clavanistic M
e
thodist preacher of the type of Edward Matthews voting Tory. So he decided that he - when he come that night he wouldn't be in the house, he was to - for - Marga, if he asked where he was - and there were benefit clubs and they paid the benefit every - it
 
was - it was to do with the works, they'd pay this every Saturday night, the people of the work - the work people, and - he said, if Mr - well what am I going to tell Mr Matthews, 'cos he'll be waiting to have supper, she says. Oh you tell him, he said, t
