\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did your mother take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Not - not publicly. But she was very interested in reading, she'd read everything about them, all the speeches. She was - my father - my grandfather was very interested in - in politics. And he'd come home - 
my grandmother couldn't read, she'd been frightened by a bull when she was a child, see, and she suffered fits, and she - she hadn't been able to go to school because of these fits as a little girl she was - and he used to - read out to her you see. He wa
s
 the man that everybody go to, as I tell you, he was the solicitor of Carmarthen, and everybody would go to the - engine room, to - Hopcyn Davis, to hear the latest news and - he'd give the news. And Mr Gladstone was in power then. Dear me, says - my gran
d
father. Mr Gladstones gone and given a swipe to her - her ladyship today. She was Queen Victoria. Queen - and she couldn't bear Mr Gladstone because Disraeli was the favourite. And - she'd said - he had said something rather sharply to her in an interview
.
 And she said, do you realize who you are speaking to? She said to Gladstone. You are speaking, she said, to the Queen of Breat Britain, of the Dominions overseas, Empress of India and so on, and she gave all the titles. And he let her go on. Yes, very we
l
l, he said, do you realize who you are speaking to? You are speaking to the people, he says, of all Great Britain, of India, and the dominions overseas, he said. And I'm the voice of the people. And I have a right also, the people that put us in, they are
 
behind us, they are - the country, the dominions overseas, he said, and I have a right, as the - Premier of the country to say what I think too. So he said, my, he flattened the old lady that day. And mother could - could always remember these, you know, 
the talk about the Liberals and the Tories. Yes, she was very interested. Oh she was very interested. And could take it in and loved reading the speeches you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What do you think her views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh I - I think - she was - not so - so severe as
 my father was on - well, he was - so dominant in it, my mother - if - if - if somebody on the Conservative had made a good speech and it was a - something to the welfare of the people - she would give him credit, she was a very very fair woman like that.
 And she liked to watch a character. She was a great believer in character you see. If he had a strong character and was a good living man - she - but I think she always voted Liberal.
