\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When did your father get home from work in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well now it was three shifts you see. Six 'til two. Two 'til ten. Ten 'til six in the morning. I
t was a hard - hard work at that - in those days, because I mean now the facilities improved, the machineries different, it was really hard work in the tin works then. I saw my father coming home very often having to sit out in the back garden, to - to ge
t
 his voice when he came home. And - he'd have to go to bed and - before he could eat his dinner. You know, he'd have his dinner ready, mother would have a good hot meal for him ready, but he'd have to rest, it - it - it was such hard work with all the hea
t and that you know in the - in the works, that he'd have to have a little rest before he - and then go to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would he walk home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Walk home, yes. And they wore little white aprons and - they'd have a special shirt in the tin works then, you kno
w, when he was a roller man. A little short shirt and - I've watched them many times putting the - sheets of tin you know in the rollers and they had these big long tongs and they'd throw them down, they'd bend them over, they had a special boot - with - 
n
ails in this boot - and they'd - red - this red hot sheet would come through, from the - from the - furnace, and they'd roll - they'd turn it over, then throw it back into the roller. Very interesting it was. But it was much harder work then than it is no
w, different entirely now.
