ely companies would come to the New Theatre you know, all the crack companies and they'd all say what a wonderful stage it was, pretty little theatre. Would seat eighthundred and - but they said it had an ideal stage, it was a shame it was set on fire, it
 was a pity the council didn't take that over, it was in such a central position as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And did you go to concerts before you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, anything that was going on in the town, concerts with the school, concerts in the town, always we
nt to - the - the town choir, they always performed great - great works. The Municipal choir. Oh yes, Municipal choir. And I can remember Mr Tommy Davis, I was in the - oh that's going too far back - too far on now - belonged to the Municipal choir as we 
got older, but - oh they were a marvellous choir, used to compete in the - in the eistedfodds and they won several times.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you go to any music halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 There was one in the old - they called it the old public hall years ago, the Gran, that wa
s a variety theatre, and of course the New Theatre had variety too, that's where Else - Gracie Fields came out first, in Mr Tower of London - was in this New Theatre. That's where she made her name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you have gone to any music hall when you were in school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Very few then, very few - when we were in school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was there any cinema while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, the Ford Road, that was very popular. And - afterwards of course - my husband came there as a musical director from N
ottingham, then there was the Grand Theatre, that was turned into a cinema.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That was after the war though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, but - no, the - the Capital was before the war. Can remember seeing the old films - coming Through the Rye, the Heckworth Film Compan
y were in being then. Henry Edwards, he was one - he was the big star, oh we - we thought he was wonderful. Henry Edwards was one of the big stars in the Heckworth films.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You would go to the cinema while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, very little though it was in those days you know, when we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5374819\charrsid2636949  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
pence a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you have it regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What would you spend the money on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well - on the way to school we'd buy - there was a little shop on the way - a Mrs David she was a widow, she came to our church - a - a}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5374819\charrsid2636949  very - we'd have this long - Sp}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 anish - strings of Spanish you know, and then - or we'd buy - there was a l
ittle boxes of what we called cocorinak, it was a mixture of cocoa, you see, and - water then there was a little spoon in it, and we'd eat that. Then there was this - sort of - it was a - really a - a herb it was - oh for the life of me I can't remember t
he name of that now, but you - you'd suck it, it was like a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5374819\charrsid2636949 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949  wood}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5374819\charrsid2636949  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 pulp and had a very - very queer taste.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was that the Spanish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, it wasn't Spanish. No, it wasn't Spanish. I can't remember the name, it was like a - a bark of a tree. And it's 
like - you'd eat - you'd suck it and it was like strings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Li}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5374819\charrsid2636949 qu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
orice stick we used to call it I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, not li}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5374819\charrsid2636949 qu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 orice stick. It - it was - a - Spanish root perhaps that's what it was, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 It used to go fibrous at the ends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That's 
right. And you'd suck this, yes. You - you - yes, we used to have that. And of course - the sugar mouse - mouse and sugar pig you know whatever -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Sweets you'd spend the money on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh we always sweets, yes, usually sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Not on going to the cinema or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, because my - our parents - my mother would give us money to go there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after her house or family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. She did all herself, only when the children were born she'd have help then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who would come then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Well - her sisters were not married in Carmarthen, you see, they were a large family, seven sisters and - the younger ones would come down, they were dressmakers, so mother would pay them - what the
y'd lose on the dressmaking to come down and look after her you see, yes, and the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 They'd be dressmaking at home would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, yes. And - I tell you another thing used to happen then. They'd go out to houses and particularly if - 
if somebody had died and wanted rush mourning, they'd go to that house - to do the sewing. Oh yes, yes. After the person had died - they'd have this - they'd go to a bedroom - in that house to do the sewing and mourning so that they could - fit the relati
ves, 'cos mourning was such a big thing then, deep black, everything black, and they would do a lot of dressmaking in the houses, that way. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did people draw the blinds in those days for funerals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh dear me, yes, everybody. Everybody
 in the street, in respect to the dead would draw the blinds. Oh quite the thing. Yes. Oh yes. They were very very respectful to the dead and - and very sympathetic, and - I can always remember when I was a little girl we in our - our denomination, I thin
k
 - I think it was held with all the - all the Welsh churches, what we called a Gwynus, that was a - a - a - night before the funeral they'd hold a - a prayer meeting service in the house where the person had died, with the family, and the - the members of
 the church, the elders and members would go there with the family and - hold prayers meetings, and prayer to us - for God to sustain the people and - prayer for the one who had passed on, that was quite a night the night before the funeral.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You wouldn't stay up all night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh no, no, no, not like the Irish, no celebrations, it was just a - a religious service, as if you were in the chapel. Oh that was quite a night, every - there always - when somebody would die in the church - down to the night -
 that night, I can remember it as a little girl going to an aunt of mine in West End who had died, my father's brother's wife had died Antue Mary Jane, and - I can remember outside the - door, listening to the service. House full, passage and - oh - yes, 
oh it was packed, every room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would there be singing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes. Oh singing, just like a prayer meeting in the church. Oh it was lovely. It wasn't very nice - I - I felt it was cruel to the relatives, but it was very touching, although it was a great c
omfort to them. But I thought it was such a mark of respect. And - that they would go and hold this meeting with the - for the relatives and the dead,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 It would only be the members of the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Yes. Or - or relatives of - of the family 
then would be there you see, it was quite a night oh and - they'd have the loan of chairs from the other houses to seat everybody 'cos they wouldn't have enough in the house for the people you see, but oh - I can remember in the passages people - the crow
ds were standing, full of the house. Standing in this service and the singing was beautiful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When your mother did have help it would be her sisters from Carmarthen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, her sisters always. When - having babies, yes. They were the only help she'd have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Not neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No. Oh yes. Neighbours were very kind, they'd come and take the washing and - come back washed and ironed. Oh wonderful neighbours, it was a - very very close knit community you know. Neighbours were very kind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 There was only Blod younger than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You told me the story about when she was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, about her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would one of your aunts be there then from Carmarthen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh they'd be there. Yes. Well two of my aunts - two - two lot
s of my aunts, I can remember the last two - married the same day from out house in Park Street, it - by - and their men - they married in a registry office in Neath because they wanted to go quietly, and I can remember - they'd go - they went in a handso
m
e cab, from our house to the station, you see, to meet their - the - then they'd meet the men in Neath, their husbands-to-be and they'd come back to ours, my mother always made the reception in our house. And two - two lots - four sisters married like dou
b
le weddings then. You see. But I can remember the last - Auntie Gwen and Auntie Elizabeth. That going from our house, I was very young, watching them going, oh beautifully dressed, they were very - they were very tasty, they loved dress, and being dressma
kers of course they were in the - I can't remember their rigs, their rig-out. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Why would they go from your house rather than Carmarthen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well they didn't want - a crowd, my grandfather you know was getting on and - his health had broken down, he suffered from }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5374819\charrsid2636949 dropsy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
 and he couldn't go to bed in the nights or anything and - they didn't want to make a big fuss in the house you see, so mother was always at hand, she was such a good one to entertain, well two sisters, Auntie Anne and Auntie Cathr
yn went from our house, and Auntie Elizabeth and Auntie Gwen. Two double weddings from our house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did they stay in your house the night before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh yes, come down the night before, not to show - not to make a fuss, they didn't want to dra
w - the - they used to go very quietly years ago, my mother went very quietly like that, because - I remember she went to Neath and with her walking, my grandfather in his top hat, oh - he was a very smart man my grandfather was and - in his frock coat, t
o
p hat, walking from Carmarthen over the Bulch, right over to Neath, to the Neath Registry Office and then he met a cousin of his in Neath after the wedding now - in Neath and they went to her house and that's what they had for the meal were kippers from N
eath market. What a wedding breakfast of kippers. And - it was a cousin of my grandfather's, and she was a very love - a lovely person. And they went back then to Scewan, and then - came back home after the wedding.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Why would they marry in a Registry do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
I don't know, that was the thing then to be quiet. To have a quiet wedding. They'd go to the Registry. Oh it was quite the thing then to marry in the Registry Office. And always Neath of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 If your mother was ill at any time how would she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh well the neighbours or her sisters would come down then. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 My - my father's parents were. His father and mother lived in West End. At - down there. And - his s
isters all lived in Taibach. Mrs Touch, My Auntie Anne, Auntie Sarah, Auntie Anne, Mrs Dyer you know, lived in Prudrith Street. Oh yes, they all lived around there, all his parents - all his rela - my mother's parents were in Carmarthen you see, and they'
d come down from Carmarthen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That was about two miles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh three, three miles, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How much did they see of their relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - often. Every week. I can remember - mother saying when - when Davy Hopcyn - he came a twelve month a
fter she was married, and my - my father - developed typhoid fever - when he was eighteen months old. Well then of course they took him, her sisters, to Carmarthen you see. The baby. And - of course the mothers then used to feed them themselves on - on th
e
 breast you see. And she nearly broke her heart, she'd walk up all the way from Taibach dying to see him you see, and - he was a lovely child I suppose, lovely baby, and - he wouldn't recognise here when he'd gone - when she'd go up, and she'd come back b
r
oken hearted. My father was home like that you see when he had this typhoid, and nobody allowed to come in and all that and a funny thing that happened - James Singleton's mother - Kitty like - Kitty Singleton - Pauper Kitty they used to call her, she - a
n
d Doctor Davis they thought - it went to his legs and they thought it - they'd have to - remove his leg. He had a terrible - he always had a bad leg after that, they called it slow fever in those days, see, not typhoid. And she'd heard now that they were 
talking about taking - so she came out across and she said to - to man, look here, she said, don't listen now about hav}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7490097\charrsid2636949 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
ng, she said, Davy's leg off she said, I've got a remedy for that. And she went out and picked ivy leaves, made - made a poultice of ivy 
leaves, put it on his leg and father's leg came beautifully, through this poultice of ivy leaves. See, always a - people were kind that way, they'd all come and - and - oh her mother-in-law was a very angelic person, she was very kind, my father's mother.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And living right by?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. Right near. Very very near.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 So you'd see a lot of your father's people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh quite a lot. But she'd see her people, they'd come down to her, and she'd go up-to Carmarthen you see always once a week to 
her - my grandfather, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would she take you all up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes. We all - and of course - there were no trains years ago, not buses or anything else, had to walk all the way from Taibach up to Pennacar to Carmarthen you see. And never - didn't think anything of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And walk back of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And walk back. Oh yes, they were very close in those days, families. Very close.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did your parents have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Always a houseful of people. Plenty of friends, plenty of - neighbours 
and; friends coming in to have a little chat you know and - and my mother was on call for everybody. She was a marvellous woman for people in sickness - because Doctor Davis used to say - that if she had - gone in for nursing or the medicine she would hav
e
 been a marvellous organiser, that's what he used to say, 'cos she was with him so many times, and when a baby would come - mother would be on call with these friends who were having these babies with the - and if it was a bad case Doctor was called, see,
 
with the midwife and mother, and - but mother said he was a very remarkable character - of course you won't remember, he had this top hat and his frock coat and he'd come on a landau and his - his driver Mr Turpin like a statue on the - in the dickey seat
 
as we used to say and dressed immaculately, this lovely uniform and he was in his top hat as well with a fawn coat I can remember, and Doctor Davis always wore a rose - in his coat. In the summer it would be a grey frock coat, and a grey top hat. In the w
i
nter black. And he would always go to prayer before he'd deliver a baby. And his one boast was that he never lost a baby or a mother. He didn't either. Oh, by the way, there was a - there was - this programme Doctor Price. Now my mother saw Doctor Price w
h
en she lived in West End, coming from the station to a man who lived in the side, you the side of Occonston, we used to call it the Side, in the mountain. Now this woman suffered, now he - I was shocked when I saw this programme last week on television ab
o
ut Doctor Price. A man who had been a - an alcoholic and that - he said, what's wrong with you, he said, you've got a frog in your stomach, and he - it was true. He - he - he gave him something that sicked the frog up. Well now then this woman up in the S
ide had a tapeworm. He was a specialist on tape}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7490097\charrsid2636949 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
work. In - very well known in those days. Well Doctor Price came from the station and he was dressed in a green corduroy rig-out with this fox hat with a tail hanging down, of course he was the first man to cr
emate a child, of course he was put in jail for it if you remember, well that was the first cremation we ever heard and - everybody now going up on the road to watch this Doctor Price going to the Side to this woman. Well anyway, he came one - one week. A
n
d he told them to - and she was going - she was fading away, because this tape worm was taking all the substance of the - of the food she was taking you see, so he - he said to starve her for a week, and they did, he come back the following week and they 
w
ere to prepare a steak - you see. And he said, not to cook it until he came. So he came - oh hundreds of people watching him coming, he was such a character, to see this Doctor Price. And when he went there he put this steak now before the fire, sort of a
 - for a grill or a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7490097\charrsid2636949 D}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
utch oven or something that they used then, and he put it to her mouth. And - low and behold the tapeworm came up, it - she was starving now for food and this tapeworm was, and he caught the head, and he cured that woman and she lived f
or years after that. He cured that woman of that tapeworm. He was a specialist in that sort of thing. He was a remarkable man.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Your mother remembered that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 She remembered that well. And what he was dressed in, green corduroy suit with this - ve
ry queerly dressed with a bread and this - big red - fox - hat, and - yes, but of course that was what he was dressed in last week in the film.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Where did your parents see their friends mainly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh in the house. They'd come - they'd visit to the h
ouse. And they'd visit them. I tell you Mrs Jones, remember Mrs Lizzie Jones and as we used to say, Mrs Morgan, Evelyn and Esther's mother, Esters birthday was on - on - Boxing Day. Boxing - I told you about that. We'd go there for the party and they'd co
me to us in January.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 She was your mother's friend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Great friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 More so than your father's, your mother would have different friends from your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well of course my father - Joseph Jones worked in the work too as a tin man with m
y father you see. And of course the two - when they were courting they'd come down to our house to do their courting before they were married, in West End.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 The girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, Mrs Jones. Mrs Jones. And Joseph. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Your mother was already married then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh she was married, and she got very friendly now when she came to Dyffryn of course with Mrs Jones and she was very intelligent woman always remember, and - they'd come down there and of course they were having children together and wer
e very very friendly Very friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did your mother and father always share the same friends do you think or did your mother have friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh they usually had the same friends, the - they were always with a husband and wife it was then you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Your father wouldn't have any friends of his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Not really, only when he'd go to the park you know with a - with - now - you know Katie, Miss - Miss Evans died last week, well now her father was a very witty humourous man and they'd
 meet in the park, and of course - on a Monday after the Sunday the discussion was the sermons in the chapel because they came to the same chapel, and he was a very witty man and my mother would say, who'd you - who did you see today in the park? Oh Davy 
E
vans, he said, what a card he is. He was telling us a story, he said, about a Welshman and an Irishman and - they met in Trafalgar Square in London. And the Irishman said to the Welshman - oh - a man from where 'ee be then? Oh, he said, I'm a Welshman, fr
o
m Wales. Oh, he said - well - where are you from then? Says the Welshman to him. Oh I be from Ireland. Oh yes. Bit talker aren't you, says the Welshman to the Irish. What - of course you are big singers, you be a big singers don't you, he said, in - in Wa
l
es? - Oh yes, and we have bars too. What do you mean by bards, said the Irishman. Naking rhymes. See, he couldn't remember - couldn't say poetry, making rhymes. What do you mean, he said, by making lines? Well, let me see now, he said, how can I tell you 
n
ow? Um - oh, you see that four lions now, in Trafalgar Square? Yes, very well he said. Well, now, then I'll make lions on those lions. Four British Lions lying on their flat, Tw yr ocher in, two yr ocher that. So that's the story's that they - he was a ve
ry amusing man. And that's the sort - the friends they were. And they used to have a whale of a time the men of course, and they were usually men that went to our church you see, all working with my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were friends ever invited into the home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh - the homes were open doors to everybody you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How often would you say you had friends in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - every day there was somebody in and out. Oh always, always - always a houseful, it was a - quite an open door for everybody. And ver
y fond of music, well - there was an old character living in West End, he's Steven Hughes, and he loved his drink, his pop you know, and he was always tight. And he - you know the old bridge down - as you go down to West End, underneath the railway line, 
w
ell this old Steven Nughes now had had quite a whale of a time and he was too drunk really and he - he sat now - or laid down then, and under the bridge. And the policeman came along and he said - now come on, come on, he said, stir up, stir up. What are 
y
ou doing here lying in the cold, he said, under this bridge? I don't know, he said, what I'm doing here. He said, well where do you come from? Piano street. Well what is Piano Street? That was West End. Now - if one would have a piano the other'd buy a pi
a
no. It was quite a competition in West End, with one would buy a piano - the whole lot and he - he called it Piano Street, because everybody owned a Piano there. And it was a very very long lively musical street you see 'cos they all put their children to
 play the piano, to learn to play the piano, and some of them couldn't bear it and their parents would lock them in the front room, they'd go out of the window to play you see. In the middle of the lessons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 If your parents had friends to the house would they be offered anything to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes, you'd never go out - without - a cup of tea was put on the hob and - something to - to eat or - or - offered - ginger wine sometimes. It was gin with the ladies you know. Gin - oh gin with the women
. I can remember one of them held a party. And - it was a childrens party again and she was a case, she - she was Mrs Lewis, she had a - a bake house in West End, Mrs - this Mrs Lewis, and - my mother was - and Dinah Griffiths next door, they were the two
 
clowns you see, that - they're the lively ones of West End, and - they went to this party and this Mrs Lewis said, now Dinah said that nothing would make her titht, you see. So she said, we'll have a game with her one day. So - this Nrs Lewis, filled a bo
t
tle full of water which looked like gin and she gave all the women - other women water, but gave gin to Dinah you see. Well now Dinah was out for the count by the time she had finished and - well of course they had to bring her home in a state, and all th
e
 women are - and - and I can remember - remember my mother saying that Mr Griffiths came in and was disgusted with my mother for allowing - and that's all she was saying, she was paying twenty shillings to the pound for everything she was buying, it's all
 
the sense he got out of her, lying on the couch, saying this, gone - tight to the world you know, and he couldn't understand why were they sover and Dinah tight. But of course they'd given her gin, they'd drunk water you see. Tricks like that they were, i
t was a - a very - \{BLANK\}
 Another story from West End, the lively women, what a wonderful community it was. There was a - a lady kept a - old lady, Bauber sis they called her. She kept a little gro - a shop and it was always smelling of red herrings. And -
 she sold a bit of everything, fish - and her husband had brakes, well now he had ordered this new brake and it was such a big brake that two horses would have to drew this brake which was very unusual. And it had cushions and oh it was very posh. So Bobo
u
s Ciss now was related to Dainah Griffiths next door my - to my mother, so Bobous says - sent a message round to say that Steven had come down with a new brake, would they like to come out to see it, and it was washing day, and they were in the middle of 
w
ashing, with the canvas aprons now before them you see washing, so they were - and Dinah said, let's go up and see Steven's new brake. So they went. And - Steven said to them, go up, try it, try the new cusions, oh beautiful - two horses in - in ready now
.
 So they went up in the brake and as they went up Steven Hughes went on the dickey seat and drove them, from - from West End, up to Porvost End, through the town, in these canvas aprons. But when they went back to West End it went hue and cry now that my 
m
other and - Mrs Dinah Griffiths were in this brake, and when they came back the flags were out and the tins were being knocked, the bread tins now, giving a reception to the brake and the two ladies in the brake. That's the sort of fun they used to have y
ears ago, great fun
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would your father and mother invite people in on particular days or any special occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, every party - every birthday the children, the children were given tea first, and then the grown ups afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you say that the friends invited in were your mother friends or your father's friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh they were all connected with the two. They were always - someone which my father and mother were friendly with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did friends call in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, there was somebody in and out all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 There was no special time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No. Oh no, no. And usually they'd knock, the door and walk in. They were that real friendly, but they knock - knock at the door in case of course there w
ere no bathrooms to the houses, in case somebody was having a bath or something, you know by the fire it used to be then in years ago when you had a house - the first houses that had no bathrooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did you do if somebody was bathing and somebody knocked at the door?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh well of course, mother would go to the door quickly and take them to the other room. Yes. Oh always knock the - the living room door, they would never come right in, but they'd come to the front door, and then they'd knock the 
living room door before they'd come in, and wait. Yes, very.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Neighbours would come in like that as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Neighbours, oh yes, neighbours. And there was one neighbour -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 They would knock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, yes. And one neighbour she'd always come
 in at mealtime though and it used to annoy my mother a bit, and she wouldn't join in, and mother liked people to join in, with the meal. No, and she'd stand in the door you know, while you were having food. She was the only one that used to annoy my moth
er I think that lady - because she wouldn't join in a meal and stand and - you feel so embarrassed when you're eating with somebody looking on and wouldn't join in, used to - disgust my mother a bit. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did your parents ever go out to visit friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Lots of neighbours. They were so close in those days you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would your father go out with your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Yes. Yes, always - they always went together. And another big thing they'd do - if there were any sick 
members of the church or friends. Oh wonderful sick visitors. And if there'd been a gymanfa ganu or something now I remember they used to go to Mrs Wellington in Alma Terrace and - she was - in the corner with rheumatism and she loved to see them coming a
nd mother then would sing the hymns of the gymanfa ganu you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements, what do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends and neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yarns you kn
ow, spinning yarns and - things that happened in the past you know or - a - or their courtship days. It was always very enjoyable conversation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would they make music do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, they weren't all very musical but of course my mother was bu
t - there was always music in our house and of course it would always be in the front room then, entertained with music you see 'cos my - elder brother would play when he was very young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would they play games do you think if they went out visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, it - it was always a conversation - with the - with the elder people, but the children would play games of course.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Many people divide society into different social classes or groups, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people belon
ging to one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes, there were - was a distinction - between the - the - cracher as we say in Welsh, the - the well to - the well-to-do and - the bosses now in our church, the elders of our church at that time were - were all of 
them either owners or bosses in the various works you see. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You wouldn't have an ordinary workman as an Elder?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - no, in the latter years that came, afterwards. It was always these - big noises that were the Elders of the church. And in
 the latter years - the years - I can remember them when I was very small of course, they brought in the Elders - from the working class - work - working class. Because the families grew and - and they used to vote you see and then they'd vote - a man tha
t
 - that they thought was a good man, fit to sit you see - but - in the - in the beginning of our church - it was a Mr Davis, Mr Edward Davis, he was the Senior Elder who owned the Prudrith Works, then there was Mr Griffiths the Bridge, as we called him, h
e
 was a big noise in the Vyvyan works, the boss, Mr Vincent - Vincent was a - Vinten I should say was another boss - in the works and - oh the - who else was there now - lots of them. Then there were the miner bosses, like Mr Rees Rees, who had a brother -
 
brother-in-law, Mr - Evans Llewellyn, I don't know whether I told you that story about him did I, Mabonne? I told you that story. Well now he - he came in - as a workman. Working man. Yes. And rees Rees of course, Rees Reese was a bit of a boss in Vyvyan 
Works. But they were - they - they - oh they were very - and then there was Mr Tom - Mr Thomas the shop, he was somebody in those days, he had a drapers shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you feel in Taibach in those days that there were different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What do you think the different classes or groups were? Before 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh there were - those who were trying to educate the children and that, there would be others who - the - they would - they would stick in the same - the children - if the father was a 
miner the boy had to be a miner, that tupe. Then there were the other type now like - my parents, wanted to give - leave the world - let - let us have a - a better place in the world than they had, you know, wanted to educate us a bit you see to get on a 
b
it. Well - there were that type, then there were the higher - higher class people who were - money people, who could afford to send their children away to boarding schools and college, now Mr Edward Davis, remember Mr Willie Arthur Davis - remember him do
n
't you, well he was the son of Edward Davis. And then Mr Joun Davis, Johnny Davis Porthcawl went afterwards, he was - he was the - Secretary of the church and - Superintendant of Sunday school and the - and the - vestry. But they were away in boarding sch
o
ol, and my mother can remember now in the old Dyffryn before this one was built, see, 'cos our church was established as I mentioned before in - 1764, in the barn, well then they built the first Dyffryn. Well then - where the vestry is now is part of the 
o
ld dyrffryn, and - the boys would come home now from this private school, it was a private school in Newport, it belonged to our denomination - one of our great preachers, a Doctor Williams, and they were - these - the - Mr Edward Davis's boys, and they w
e
re considered the hob nobs of Port Talbot and the church, and they'd come back from school and they'd come in their mortar boards and Eton suits, you see. And - they had a fashion mother said the windowsills of throwing their mortar boards us on the windo
w
 sill, and this Babous Ciss, Taibach now - her sister was in service with Edward Davis you see, and they'd all look forward now to see them coming you know to chapel and - when - when they're home on - on leave from the board - boarding school, and she sa
id - in the shop one day, did you see Edward Davis's children home from school yesterday, they came with their dinner plates on their head. And that's how it was, witty you know, very - very -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you feel the Elders in the chapel were in a different class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes. And another thing, the respect to the church now - do you know as a little girl, you know, we have a big seating our denomination - as all the Welsh non-conformist churches have, and the pulpit, well do you know, I - I - I was - that -
 in so much awe in the church I was afraid to put my foot in the big seat in - going to the pulpit was unthinkable, that was holy of holies. Oh yes, and - and the men that were in the big seat, oh we looked up to them, they were somebody. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were there any people in Taibach then who didn't go to any place of worship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes, there were a - there were quite a few but - mostly people - went to - belonged to some church or other - in Tabiach. Can't remember them many - only the - people who had come
 from say - England and that sort of thing or had come from Birmingham, you know, some people now lived next door to us, the Cleavers, he was a boss in the Vyvyans Work you see, they never went anywhere, and - I can remember - she had a lodger, Mr Street,
 
and he was putting out - up a greenhouse, see, and hammering on a Sunday. Much to my father's disgust and my mother. And Mrs Cleaver over the wall she was one to make fun of us going to church you see, she was that type and I don't think she ever went to 
a
 place of worship and very deep accent, deep - Birmingham accent - accent, and - she said, I suppose you heard the banging, she said, yesterday in the - yes, my mother said, and I'm very disgusted, she said. You disturbed our Sunday. She said, fancy, she 
said - putting up a greenhouse on a Sunday, unthinkable here in Wales. You see. The respect to the Sunday was terrific. And we as children felt the same, but - even - putting your foot - I wouldn't put my foot on the big seat even, it was too - sacred.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Which class or group would you say you belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh the - sort of the - middle class I should think we were, you know, were a - my mother had got us to a - pitch I think that - she wanted to give us a bit more than the ordinary people then. She liked us to rise above the ordinary. She -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What sort of people belonged to the same group as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh there were lots of nice people. Lots of people that came - in our church who - there were there were several groups that way, some very ver
y ordinary and the others you know like Mrs Jones, my mother's friend, she brought her family up, educated them, would do anything for - to educate the children to give them a better life you see. To rise the standard of living then, and they were intelli
gent you see from the ordinary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What sort of people belonged to the other groups or classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 The - well you mean the higher now or the low?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, and yes low.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - oh they were - very very ordinary and - and - uncouth some - you know, v
ery ordinary and - I don't know, they were a type that you wouldn't like to mix with then, you see, and then there were these - big noises. Now this Edward Davis family, when we'd have a - anniversary in our chapel, they'd go to Paris to buy their rig out
s
. And I - I can remember one year - now - this was the only fault that we had with them. You were not supposed to dress anything, and my mother was very fond as - from young on to have a - to dress nicely. And her sisters being beautiful dressmakers you s
e
e and she'd been to Ben Evans to buy the material for this frock, it was quite an event, the anniversary. And - she bought this material in Ben Evans's, and she had picked the style from the fashion books as we do today, you see, it was fashion books then
,
 not a big book like you have - what do they call them today now, McCalls and - Butterick and all that, no, it was a magazine that would come out every month, a fashion book, the fashion book, Wildens, that was the big fashion book in those - well my moth
e
r had chosen this style and my aunts, beautiful dress - dressmakers had made this lovely frock and my mother was of a - very very slim, very smart person when she was young it appears, because in the latter years when she went stouter she used to call her
 
- she used to say, don't look at my fore and after it was you see. Well - she'd got stouter. But she was very very slight, very very small waist and - a small foot, and - a mop of black hair. Well - she had this frock and she had a little - a little hat -
 
bonnets they were, and she was describing this bonnet she brought - bought it in Swansea, and on the bonnet was a - a purple - purple and multi stock - stocks on it and a - a butterfly, of sequin in green, perched on this semi-stock, and she created quite
 
a sensation now and listen - and Mr Edward Davis's family now - had seen my mother in this frock, you see, and they had come from Paris - and the Miss Hughes's in Meiser Court, well they are dressmakers. The three Miss Hughes's were lovely dressmakers, an
d
 because - and - unfortunately for my mother - or fortunate - or - or take it as you like, anyway I want to show now the snobbery a bit was then you see. Went to the dressmakers, they were called over the coals, why had they made that frock for myc mother
 
like theirs. And they said they hadn't made it, that Mrs Davis had had it made by her sisters, and - she had chosen it from the same book as they had, and that she had quite the same right to choose any frock she liked like they did, but anyway the disgus
t
 of those now that my mother - a working man - in the - in the tin works, should dress in the same style dress as they were you see. He was the owner of the works. Yes, he went bankrupt then, went very poor unfortunately then 'cos they were - he was a lov
e
ly man Mr Davis was, but the wife was a bit of a snob you know and - you weren't supposed to follow the family in any way, not that my mother tried to, she didn't know - she was going to have a frock of that style. So there was a class distinction then. S
ee?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about the people who were not in the chapel in Taibach, did you have much to do with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Not a - oh yes, friendly with a lot of church people - Holy Cross was a big thing then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was there a distinction between them and the chapel people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh no. No, no. Only that of course the - chapel people would boast to the church people that - the preaching wasn't nearly as good with them as it was with us, the non-conformists you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What sort of people would you say went to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh very nice people. Very nice people. They were all nice people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about people going to the chapel, would they be different, people going to the church and going to the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well - different in religion, in their form of re
ligion. But I wouldn't say they were different people. They - their mode of living was much the same. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh no. No. We were taught at home tha
t we were to like - particularly to respect old people. Oh yes, that was drummed into us. We had - we had to help old people as much as we could and children, but particularly old people, we were always trained that we were supposed to be respectful and h
ave good manners, always to respect the old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were you ever told to curtsey?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No, I can't remember curtseying but - I can remember mother saying that - when she first came down from Carmerthen when she first married they always curtsied to Doctor Davis, and to a minister of the gospel, any minister. Or Doctor Davis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Your mother did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh no. No, she never curtsied. No, it - it had gone out by then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh rise their caps - and rise their caps for a funeral had to stand
 - when a - if a - a body - a funeral was passing, especially when the body went past, rise their caps and bow their heads and stand, they weren't supposed to walk when it was passing, and - always trained to do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who would the boys touch their caps to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh - everybody they looked up to now - the bosses of course, the - their father's bosses or - any - any - any Elder or - of the church, or anybig noise in the - in the - in Taibach, they always raised - and the schoolmaster and the teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was there anyone you called sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
We called - always called the schoolmaster sir, and the boss - whoever was - the boss, the - the - like my father would say sir to his - to the - to his boss you see, or any of the foremen, would say sir to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you call anyone master or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, oh yes, we'd say to - to the schoolmaster - the master or - it was more calling their}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7490097\charrsid2636949  C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 hristian - Mr - Mr Nicholas the schoolmaster, you see, in my time. But teacher for teacher, please teacher, it was always please or thank you teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh yes they'd always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who would?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Young people of the chapel or young men, they'd always doff their hats.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 In the village of Taibach who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh I think it was the - the bosses, the doctor, the schoolmasters and the teachers. Then they were considered the - particularly the schoolmaster. I don't know whether I told you that story about my brother - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7490097\charrsid2636949 mischievous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
 one when he was a boy in school, Eastern School, Taibach, when they were building the bridge for the PT railway across you know, at that time they built the bridge when he was a boy in Eastern school, - and - the scho
olmaster was called Mr Martin and he had an umbrella like a tent, huge umbrella. And there were little mounds of sand, and it had been snowing so my brother was very very mischievous said to the boys, Mr Martin's coming with his tent, let's go up on the -
 
on the embankment now and one drop sand and the other drop snow on his umbrella. Consequence was of course they broke the umbrella the seam of the - and the umbrella fell over Mr - Mr Martin's - face. And he was a - a very - strict schoolmaster and could 
c
ane unmercifully you know. So - Will now my brother - ran down now quickly now to the gate to meet Mr Martin coming, good morning sir, and saluted. They always salute this headmaster. William Davis - look at my umbrella. You must find out who the culprit 
is. And of course - somebody split on Will and he had to good flogging for it. Oh yes. But that's - that's the sort of fun we used to have years ago.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who else would you consider the most important people in Taibach?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, the headmasters or the doctor and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you come into contact with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 The bosses in the works, would you yourself come in contact with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, no, no, wouldn't come into contact with them. They were - sort of a people on their own you know. Only
 our parents would come in contact with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Why were they considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Because they owned these works, they were bosses and - the - and the doctor was a - a an on his own, and the schoolmaster was a man on his own. Oh they were entire
ly a - a - a group that - were looked up to by everybody. Because they were the educated I think - particularly the schoolmaster and the doctor and all those, they were looked up to them, but the bosses were looked up to because they were the bosses you s
ee.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about the shopkeepers, who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh - oh - with everybody, they - they had the whole of Taibach buying with them, it was a very very - busy community Taibach in those days you know because - the works, there were the t
wo tin works, there were the copper works, there - Vyvyan works. It was a very very - busy - they had a market where - you know the Mount Surgery is now at the back there, and Old Water Street used to be there and there was a big open space there and ever
y Friday night there was a market there. And it was quite a - oh quite a busy little community Friday night was a great night in Taibach.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about the shopkeepers in their off duty time, who would they be friendly with in the village, who would they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh they'd have their own particular friends, and they - the shopkeeper friend, the shopkeepers themselves would have a sort of a little community of their own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about the clergy and ministers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh they were people again
 - on their - on their own. But the clergy in those days, they were very good what we call today shepherds, they were very good for visiting. The old type. There was a man in Taibach - Mr Thomas at Vayan church, not our church, the - the - what was it - t
h
e congregation dependant church, and they used to call him the - the - vicar of Taibach. He was a lovable man and they came - his wife kept a shop, a grocers shop, and they had lots of sons who were all educated, and - very scholarly. Two of them were in 
t
he shop, one of them used to make little - little pantomimes for the children of the church and that you know, very brilliant - we used to go to Cardiff to see a show every week he did, Derry, and - I think they had - one minister son, and one of the sist
ers went out to South Africa, married, two have married ministers. But this - the - Mr Thomas Cabayan as we called him - was the most lovable man you ever met - was a - a man for every church then. Loved in Porthcawl - in Port Talbot, Taibach.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 With whom would the clergy associate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
With each other. With each other as a rule, and the vicar now, there was a - there was a - the Vicar Jones years ago in St Theodores church - now, he - Mr Williams the Printer, you remember Mr Williams the Printer, well 
now - there was Joe Cowand, do you remember Joe Cowand, lived in Abbey Road, married - Prissy Thomas, the sister - Vicar Jones, my brother Will - that Mr Thomas that was - be - I think he was the surveyor - for the - town surveyor at that time, remember h
i
m? From Margan? They'd all meet in Williams print - well Will never came home 'til twelve in the night, and with this establishment of Wales that come with Lloyd George you see, and - Will was writing articles every week, he'd hear these conversations and
 
he'd be with them, with Vicar Jones and all, they were all churchmen, and Will was anon - conformist you see. And they would have these big - Will would write these articles in the papers and they wondered who on earth it was, writing against the church f
or disestablishment, and used to have a whale of a time, oh and they - oh they were wonderful - there was a wonderful man again, Vicar Jones. Wonderful man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about the teachers, who would they be associating with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh they'd mix with the famil
ies. They - they'd - oh they - they were a very interested in some families and would come to the homes of the families - I don't know whether I mentioned before how - my mother loved to - have them in our house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 There were some farmers in Taibach then too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, Mrs - oh - Mr Jones the Farm, and - some down in Gross of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who were they friendly with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well - they were friendly with each other again, the farmers, you see, mixed with, each other. And - Josephss - Joseph - Groswen Fa
rm, now - Mrs Joseph was a very faithful member with us, and - Llewellyn Josephs were, and we'd go there to tea very often to Groswen Farm. And it was quite a treat to go up to Groswen, and we'd go to the woods to pick bluebells. As children. She was a lo
vely person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you think chapel people just associated with chapel people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Mostly. Mostly. Oh no, mostly with chapel people. Because - the chapel was - so full in those days, there was - it was such a big membership. And everybody knew each other and were friendly with each other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about the employers of the works, who would they mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh with the - with their own families, they wouldn't mix with the - workers as a rule, no. And I tell you another thing, the Elders were a sort of Semedrin, there was no court in those days, if - if say two members quarrel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
ed with each other - and - some perhaps had been abusive you see - you had - you were called before the Diachomit. Not a court, and they would sit on your case, you had to appea
r there, see. And that was the punishment, whoever was the guilty person - would be - ex - excommuni}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
ate - communicated for - three months, they wouldn't be allowed to take communication, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would they be allowed to come to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 They'd be allowed - oh yes, they could come but they weren't supposed to take communion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was that only when people quarre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 led or something or would it be in any other cases?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That - well it was a - years ago but thank goo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 ness that law's finished now, i
f a couple would - be courting for years and perhaps the girl would fall pregnant before marriage you see - they - she would be - they - the pair - couple - would be - cut adrift for three months, not allowed, and they would come - they would be allowed t
o come back memberships if they asked they were to be allowed - to come back as members, which I think was a rather a cruel thing to do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 They hauled up people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Be - before the - before the Elders. If they fell pregnant before marriage - they wer
e hauled up, the - the couple. And it was even broadcast in the chapel that they had been - excommunicated from the church for a certain period, they weren't allowed to take communion. They were allowed to come, but of course they'd be too ashamed, but th
ey'd have to ask - for re}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 membership back - after the baby was born. They were allowed to come back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would they marry in the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh no, not as a rule. They wouldn't marry in the chapel, they'd go to a - a - to a registry office to mar
ry. Oh yes it was - I don't think they'd allow you to marry if - they knew that about you you know, I don't think they'd allow you. It was terribly cruel. And you know -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Where would they have them up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - oh they had to come to a special meeting. No, no, a special meeting of the Elders. And then it would be anno}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 nced in the church that this couple - to it was terrible, it was shocking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You remember that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh I can. And it was so pathetic for that couple to face - you see, the church an
d it would take years for that to die down you see. And what a bad effect on young people, you know, it - it would give you an effect from - there was people - sinned very badly, it looked so bad to us, it was such a bad thing to do. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Where you li
ved did all the people in the working or middle class have the same standard of living or would you say there were different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. Yes, you take now these bosses that live in posh houses and - and the middle class were trying - come up from th
e smaller house to a bigger house, but there was still this - lower class, the three classes you could say just as it is now. The lower, the middle and the high ups, you see. Just as it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You couldn't describe a family within each of the groups, you have really described Edward Davis haven't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. Well - then there was a - a group -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Where would Edward Davis live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh he lived in a - in - where - Doctor Davis's - Doctor Phillips's surgery was down in Taibach. And - the - the old women
 of the church would - be allowed - they'd go on Saturday - to - with - they had maids of course to - to clean the vegetables ready for Sunday, the old widows and they'd be given a shilling for that and some of them would be invited to dinner, not with th
e
 - not to sit with the - with - with the family of course, they'd have to sit in the servants quarters. But they'd be given a - a - a shilling to - and - you know, clean the vegetables on the Saturday ready for Sunday. It was always done on a Saturday. Mi
nd we as families in churches used to do that. The - the families, the ordinary families, would always clean the vegetables on Saturday. Because Sunday as I say was a day at home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You mentioned Mr Edward Davis's sons went away to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Had he any daughters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes. There was Edith, and they were all - one married a doctor, one married a minister, one married a bank manager, one of his daughters - Annie I think, Miss Annie Davis, she was the organist - the first organist of Dyffryn 
- when a pipe organ was first installed in Dyffryn - from the harmonium. Of course - my mother can - when she first came down to Dyffryn can remember - no organ at all, a big shock. And that's who used to have the pitchfork was Mr Richard Hopcyn, his - hi
s uncle. Will - Edward Hopcyn and he had a Sunday school and he was the - the what we say, he used to be with the sin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
ing you see, the conductor, and he had a pitchfork and he he'd be in the big seat and he'd hit this pitchfork says my mother and he'd say, 
doh me soh doh, you see, the - in - before they start the hymn, 'til he had the right note, and - but she said the singing was gorgeous, when she came from Carmarthen first, no organ. But then the pipe organ was put in, and Mr Edward Davis's daughter Anni
e was the organist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did his daughters go away to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes, I think they did. I think they all had edu - good education. Except the elder one - the eldest one was home - with the family, she looked - when - when Mrs Davis died she used to look 
after the family then, her father 'til he died. I can remember his funeral when we lived in Park Street up at Holy Cross. Yes, oh very large funeral. We could hear the singing from Holy Cross church and - and the cemetery and it was such a large funeral -
 in our - in our house. We were outside - I was - outside - outside the house. Yes, and you could see clearly then because there was no buildings between our house and the cemetery you see, across the park. Very very large funeral.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about the next class, the middle class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Well now them - you'd call them now like - the Miss Hughes's that were the dressmakers very respectable family - people you look up to and - Mrs Jones, and - oh dear, the Rodericks, and Mr Snook and Mrs Snook. He was the trea
surer of the choir. And - your mother's family now, the - the Williams's, they were a family, you see, they - Mrs Williams, your great-grandmother - they were a family on their own again, sat near us - there were certain families that were the - that you 
looked up to - in between the lower class you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about in the lower class, what sort of families would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well now - there was a - a little man, we called him Gin Tom, he drove - you know the little railway that used to go by the ch
apel, it would go from the Byvyans work to the station, to the main railway you see, and it brought the material for the copper works along and there was a little engine - afterwards it was a horse, and - he - was a member and his wife and she was very la
m
e on a stick, she must have had rheumatism, and he - had a - was - lame, he had an accident on his leg, he broke a leg, and he was the driver and we called him Engine Tom. You see Tom - Thomas his name was lived in - in - what - Cotton Row, Taibach, where
 the Hunts lived you see. Well now they were a lower class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Why did you think they were a lower class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Well, because - you know, the - they were a family that were - didn't try - the parents didn't try to educate them, they were the type that lik
ed pain, and one of these people - were always living in a surgery with doctors and always sorry for themselves, you know, that type. Mrs Hunt always lived in a surgery, always something wrong, and always a long face, that type you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would they be particularly poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes, they were - they were - a very poor family. And there was another family, the Perry's, they were very poor, Mrs Perry would go out cleaning. And the daughters as they were growing up would go out cleaning. That was the - l
ower - they were in Cotton Row.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you think that one group felt itself superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Well this higher class as I tell you of course they - they were really what you'd call snobbish you see. Looked down - looked down on the middle class even you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were some families thought of as rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes, up the Side at the Gotstant, and up in Goitre - and some in Pennacar too mind, terrible up - we were scared of them in school, the girls and boys that would come down from those places, we were scared stiff, they'd come in gangs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Why were they like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Well it must have been the community they lived in. And their parents - were - were - mostly - not that I disregard a collier, but a - but - they were a - the type of peopl
e that are illiterate and didn't try to rise above the ordinary then even some and - oh the language - it must have been the effect of the parents or the home I think. They were terrible creatures - oh the - celluloid children were noted. We would run mil
es from them, Goitre. Oh they were terrible. And up there Side mind. You know, the Colston, that way. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were any families thought of as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh they - they would - but this lower class would - would - wouldn't half let you know
 it, they'd pelt at you and do all sorts of things because you'd - you know, they - they - they thought you were - a class above and they liked to have their - revenge on you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 In what way would they show it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - in - comin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949  in - in gangs and run after you and hammer you - hammer you yes, and - pelt stones, they would do all sorts of things, they were terrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Going to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. And coming home from school we were scared stiff of them. And they'd fight our boys you know, the boys 
in school, always fights, some black eyes you know, the children, oh my mother went in between fights like that very often, she couldn't stand children fighting. And she was always in the middle of a gang - of these children fighting you know, and soon di
spersed them you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No, it wasn't a - very noticeable mind but there was that distinction. You notice it in the church now, now this Rees Rees as I tell you is a bit o
f a boss in the Vyvyans work you see and he was - he - he had that sort of dignity - over the men in the works and they weren't very very fond of the - of the old man because he - he - he was very reserved and kept aloof from the men, oh there was that th
ere with the second - with the middle class you know. There was a bit of a distinction with the - with the - middle class to the - to the - to the lower class, the - craftsman with the ordinary labourer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you feel the middle class then was all the craftsmen, was it going by fathers job do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
I think so. It - it had to do with the job, I think, and the way the children would - would - you know - succeed in school and that sort of thing, they would look up to those families whose children
 were bright and would succeed, they'd be put in - in a church now, ooh, he's very sharp, he ought to be made Secretary or to be Treasurer. It was that sort of a - distinction you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No. No. They - they - they both of them treated - they - they were a type of people who treat everybody alike but they - of course - naturally they'd look up to their bosses, you see, there was that - distinction there, but otherwise
 no, they would make no distinction between the lower. No, they - they were very humble people. Never had that - snobbish idea that they were any better than anyone else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 I - how do you mean now, in - in a - in a - ordinary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How do you think your mother thought of herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - yes, she liked to think that she was trying to make a better world for her family. Oh yes, she'd - she was very keen on that. She'd
 sacrifice anything, she'd go without - herself to give - the children - education and to rise the family as much as she could. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you think she was thinking of her parents class or your father or his work or the house she lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. 
Well she always liked to better everything, ever her surroundings her house, and - she liked to mix in a nice society, you know, intelligent people. Everybody didn't suit her mind but she would - she would put up with them, but - she loved a conversation 
o
f in tell - I tell you it was young teachers and that would come to her you see. Young - young - educated people because they felt - she was such a prolific reader herself, and wanted - she would - she said she was never too old to learn even at ninety-se
ven. And that was her attitude throughout life, you're never too old to learn and better yourself you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
In these days when you were young was it possible to move from one class to another? Like to go from the working class, the lower class to the middle or from the middle to the upper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, if you wished to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Can you remember anybody who did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Let me think now. Oh well you take now then - we'll take Philip Jones the preacher, Brought up in a very very humble home, in Taibach, wor
ked with my father. In - in - in - in the - in the tin works then you see, but the remarkable things was a boy - he always brought - in the middle of - in - in - in the break, a meal break, he - he always had his bible out, you could see, well now then fr
om a very ordinary - illiterate - family, he rose to be one of the greatest preachers in Wales. And - you know what a gentleman he looked, he was a real aristocrat, he looked it, didn't he. Well now then that to me was very outstanding.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 He was brought up in Dyffryn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Brought up in Dyffryn church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh well he was - he was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, Mrs Williams in Palm Farm. There was a lady. She'd - there - were to see
 her walking down the - and she sat in the third seat from the front. From the big seat. And she always wore beautiful clothes, and she was a very good looking woman, and my mother always looked up to Mrs Williams Sinnafarm farm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Why do you think she was described as a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Because - her behaviour and her manner - she was such a lady. Oh yes. And I can remember mother telling her - and she was thrilled, she loved you to tell her you know, well Mrs Williams, she said, you look gorgeous yeste
rday, she had a new rig out for the big meetings or anniversaries, and I can remember she had a beautiful bonnet, and it - a big purple bow in the front, and she had beautiful colouring. She was a picture woman, and my mother said, Mrs Williams, you look 
a
 real lady, she said. And oh, Mrs - oh Mrs Davis, thank you, she said, I'm - I'm thrilled - and she'd walk from Sinnafarm Farm - to Dyffryn, and to see her walking down the aisle to her seat was really something. She was such a lady. Her carriage you know
, there's something lovely - and always a smile. Pleasure to look at her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well who could you describe as a real gentleman. Well I - I used to like Mr Snook. There was a gentleman, his - 
his speech was lovely. He was the Treasurer of the choir, and Mr Davey Malt the - attendance officer, Micher man we called him then, the Mitcher man. There was a gentleman. Now teacher Sarah's brother-in-law, he was married to her sister, and there was a 
gentleman and he was one - he was Secretary of the choir.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Why would you say he was a real gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Because of his manner, you'd never hear him rise his voice, he'd never quarrel with anyone and he had to cause to quarrel very often. And - and 
- and even the job he had which wasn't very nice was - to go round - round some parents were very - rude you know to the attendance officer would call to see where the children were. There were a lot of poor families who would keep their children home, ha
d
 no shoes or clothes perhaps in those days you see, to send them to school. But he was such a patient man. And Mr Snook - oh - it was a pleasure to hear Mr Snook, he couldn't speak Welsh - but he understood it, but to hear him speaking in English you'd ne
v
er say - that he was brought up in Wales, he - oh there was something - and he was a - a big man, a very - a very round face, but to hear him getting up to speak - and - in a meeting now and the choir you know, but those are two men I always looked up to 
as a little girl. Their manner, and their - speech, and their patience and this - this love - but Mr - Mr Snook particularly, the most happy face I ever saw.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember seeing a policeman around when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, the bobbies we 
used to say. They lived - they - they lived in Park Street, you see, and - they sat in a seat - across to us, there was a little - aisle between, and they sat in the seat - and Mrs Williams's wife was a very good looking woman. And their family were there
, Tommy, Liz - you know, manager Libby of course has passed on now, Tommy, Annie William, married to John Williams Tacklehouse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well - he - I - we - we liked him very much, but Taibach people didn't like him because he 
was very very keen after the culprits. Oh very, very keen. I think - they used to make poetry about him. Used to watch people going stealing and the houses and would expose them you see and of course he was very unpopular, Williams the Bobby. In Taibach, 
if he would expose anybody he'd caught stealing and brought up in the Court, of course he - he - his name would be mud in Taibach. Oh yes. But a very nice man. Liked him very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did your mother ever say, I'll call a policeman when you were naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes, she did. Not very often, she didn't like to throw that up very much, she didn't like us to be frightened of policemen, no. But you know she said who's sitting in the seat next to us. You know, she said, Mrs Williams the Bobby. I'll tell him a
bout you. But he was a kind man and we - we were very fond of him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You weren't frightened of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, not a bit.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How do you think he treated the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well he was a very fair}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 man. I thought - when I think about him I - I thought he
 was a very patient man with the people in Taibach, but you know there was so clannish and in Taibach. If anybody would expose someone else you see and - particularly the policeman, they didn't like it at all. No. But - but I liked him very much. I was ne
ver frightened of him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 To anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you pay rent for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh no, no, no. No, they - then my father and mother owned the house from West End on from the time they were married they went - they paid for their own 
house. Yes. Oh no, my mother wasn't one of the renters at all. And she'd never buy any goods unless she could pay for it. In furniture or anything, she'd do without - until she had the money to pay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you remember feeling that your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Well I knew my mother - if anybody was sacrificing my father was always looked - looked to in every way because - he was the breadwinner and my mother was very cautious of him for the - he wasn't a very strong man, and - we al
ways felt if there was any sacrifice made it was mother would make the sacrifice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you feel that they had a struggle at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, particularly when - my father was out of work for that two years. That was a big struggle, but I never heard my 
mother complain or grumble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did you think about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh very downhearted. We used to watch the stack, because there was talk all the time that somebody was going to buy the works you see, and the men now what - and they stopped to see if t
his smoke would ever come from the stack. We children used to watch that mind. And there was a thrill when this Evan Bevan had bought the works and we saw the first smoke for two years going up the stack. There was jubilation in Taibach, for the people th
a
t used to work in the Prudrith works. It was very prosperous then of course after that. This was a very strong firm that bought it. See, Davis's went bankrupt, they had put money in a mine, in a colliery. And this colliery failed. And that's what - brough
t them down you see, that they lost the tin works.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What difference did it make to the family when your father was out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well of course mother had to draw - draw in her horns as she said, and - sacrifice a lot, but we never were without fo
od. Never. And she sacrificed with the clothes, patch - patches up more and sew little things herself for us and - as I tell you she tapped shoes and - 'cos my father was - it was very funny, I told you about the Scotch woman coming for the last, that's b
ecause - I forgot, my father when - he was - the tin workers wore a - wore a white apron you see, yes, so it looked as if - he was a shoemaker, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did they ever get help from the Guardians or the Parish or any charity when he was out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh no. No. No dole, nothing at all. The only help - the little bit my mother had saved and struggled for, and - 'cos she - mother - daddy would earn the - the money, but man was the organizer, that's the Doctor who lives - Davis's used to tell her what 
a remarkable organiser she was you see, and you'd never hear her complain or - plead poverty, oh no, never. Never heard her say that she was - she was - oh no, then of course my grandfather would - would lend her money if she was short in any way and - of
 
course she was always so honest in the shops they would - give her the - the goods until she'd have some money from her father you see to pay up. And - oh - and she was - just used what she had. But she was very glad to - to - when the work started of cou
rse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Two years was a long time wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh it was along time, with no dole or - no help in anyway. Oh, and - because they were on the Parish then you see, people would go but my mother wouldn't go on the Parish, no, the last thing on earth she'
d do. She never was a one to plead poverty, or to ask for any poverty - for any - pittance or charity. She'd rather give than receive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When there was someone in the district whom the people disapproved of very strongly was there any special way in which they showed it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes, they'd cut them adrift. They - wouldn't bother with them. They wouldn't send them to Coventry, they'd - always pass the time of the day but - they would treat them very very short, you know, give them short shrift.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 They wouldn't be made to leave the district or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh no, they wouldn't be as severe as that. No, they were - the people were too kind for that. No, they wouldn't - no, they would never make it difficult for you. But they would - give you the cold shoulder then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 About school now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were you ever given lessons by one of your parents, a tutor or a governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. We - we - we - were - we'd be coached perhaps if we wanted to - do anything special. My mother'd pay for us to be coa
ched. Yes. But - she never took a part with - with - nor my father, unless it was something in Welsh or something in the Bible that we had to have lessons right at - or some question that had puzzled us about that of course they were very ready with that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh I must have been about four and a half to five I should think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When you first started what time of the morning did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh by nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And when did you come home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 About half past twelve I think it would be when we'd come back from school. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you have afternoon school when you first started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh no, had to go back in the afternoon. I can remember Miss Nones for the head}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 mist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 ress. Mrs Barratt Jones you know and - we 'we started first in the infants school and then - as I tell you we called our teachers by their }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
hristian names, teacher Sarah, you know, two teacher Sarah's, teacher May, teacher Jenny, teacher Dorothy and - Miss - Miss Selby, we called her
 Miss Selby it was somebody's mother' there, I don't know - why we called her Miss Selby, she came in latterly like you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was it a mixed school when you first started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, boys and girls. Yes, boys and girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 It would be a board school wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What time did you come back after afternoon school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 About four to half past four.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What time would you have gone back after dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 About two o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How did you get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh w
ell of course we lived - near the school in the West End, just had to walk - oh - a quarter - a very short distance. Few hundreds of feet it was from West End to the - school. But of course Went to Park Street a bit further, but then - when we lived in Pa
r
k Street and we went to the - Eastern School Taibach - the - the - what - what do you call it, the - what would you call the - prime - primary school, junior primary school. Taibach first of all. Junior school, Eastern, I was only there to standard two, t
hen we moved here and I went to the Temple school. Well that was a few yards that was, on the doorstep as you might say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Eastern was the furthest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That was the furthest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That would be about half a mile?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Easily. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How long would it take you to go to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh well, I was never late, I was very - only once - I ever had the cane and that was a big insult to me, that was when I was in the Central school, we - before we moved here we - we - I - I was - we had been put down at 
Central ready for the moving, and Mr Nicholas was the schoolmaster, and because I spoke Welsh he was such a Welshman that he'd always call me to - go for his messages, we were great friends, and he always wore a bowler hat. Never saw him without his bowle
r
, but very fond of his cane, and he had very shaggy eyebrows you know. And - we were walking across from the park now from my home, from Park Street across and there was a big field of Swedes here, Rakes Field, you see, and somebody had been stealing the 
S
wedes, so we were stopped to come the short way and we would say - we have to - we were ordered back with Mr Riggs and had to go right round the main road, consequence was when we got to school the doors were closed and we were locked out. Oh - and we wen
t
 now of course in the hall now to wait for our canings because everybody late was having the cane then. So - oh and Mr Nicholas, he had little beady eyes for these shaggy eyebrows, well bach, he said, in Welsh, what had happened to you? And that's the onl
y caning I ever had on my hand and I was awfully insulted. I liked - but of course he couldn't make any distinction different to me, I couldn't explain to him what had happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who went with you to school, when you were in the infants school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Because you went to three different schools didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes. In Park Street you see, I went from Park Street to the infants school. You see. Not many living around, oh there was Katie Millington.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who would take you, who would go with you to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh my mother first of all. My mother first of all. And - would always take us, or one of my brothers, you see, would take us - would take me to school, and - then - we - we'd - it was a - rather a - a step then it was - but we'd go along
 the Prudrith river, along Brook Street, Prudrith Street, up - and come out at the main road you see, wasn't very much traffic in those days of course, cross the road - and down into the school you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Where did you have your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh ho
me. Went home - yes. We'd take lunch though. For eleven o'clock. Little sandwich, bread and butter or jam or a little bit of cake. We always took our lunch in a little parcel. Yes, always when we were in the infants school. Then we'd eat that in between a
bout eleven o'clock. Yes, on playtime. Outside, not in - no, no, outside in the playground we'd eat that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh I liked school very much, yes, oh - and - and Miss Jones was very severe head - mistress, she was - she had
 her - her hair done up very much like Queen Mary would have it. And I wondered if she had a wig, it was always perfect, in perfect condition you see, and one thing that I can remember very well was the swing, you know, when I first went to school, and th
e
 rocking horse. But - what intrigued me always was they had a - a lovely red squirrel stuffed in a case, and I always went to inspect that every day, this red squirrel in a case, that's - outstanding, it was a beautiful model, with the tail standing up, o
h lovely it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you like the school or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh I loved the school. Oh I liked the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Now teacher Benny was more severe, that's - Mr Nichols - Sam Nochol's mother, I was afraid of he
r. Afraid of Miss Jones the headmistress. But wasn't afraid of your mother, not teacher May nor teacher Sarah Evans you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 I don't know, but - perhaps because we were going to the same church. I think you see I - they - they wer
e - their faces were so familiar to me, and of course they were big noises in the Band of Hope, and the - the week - with the children, that - we - we got attached to them in the church and at the everyday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh good manners was a big thing. Oh, we were taught to have good manners. And - to be - to be respectful to everybody we were taught. They were like - like - liked us to have curtsied, oh we'd always stand up when a teacher
 came in the room. Whole class would stand up. We had that respect for our teachers then, we loved our teach - I loved my teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh you had to be tidy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 We had to be careful about that too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did you speak at home, Welsh or English?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
All of us spoke Welsh, except Blod. She - got - in - with a - with an English crowd living around now when - up here now you see, I can't remember a lot about it, she was very young, up here,
 and she got in with a - with a - the English set that lived all around here, she went more into the English then. My mother spoke to her in Welsh but she answered in English, and she went to school and then she went to - a - a school in Swansea. Mixed wi
th a lot -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When you went to school in the infants at Taibach what was the language at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Welsh. All We}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 sh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What was the language in Taibach school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - mixture of Welsh and English you see, yes, mixture.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen? You had the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Or put in the corner. And dunce's hat on your head. I never had that though thank goodness. Because I - I - I think we were taught so much at home and in school and - we did appreciate g
ood manners and we tried to - we liked to behave ourselves, but there were terrors in school then you know. Wicked - wicked boys, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How did they punish them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 With the cane. They'd go out - for the cane with a teacher, or to the headmistress 
or put in a corner, depend - on the - on the - on the crime you see, whatever they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were the girls punished the same as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Cane. Give them the cane but - or put in a corner. But not as heavily as the boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What offences would they have to commit to have these punishments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 If they were rude to the teacher or if they wouldn't listen now to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh very. Oh very interested. Particularly my mother, more so my mother t
han my father. He was so quiet and - she took a great delight in everything we did in scholastic - my father would listen, but she was the one that - how did you do today? We had to - give an account of ourselves every day. And watch our reports of course
 to see how we were doing, what were the reason if we dropped in a subject, why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did they ever visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. You go down to - anything special with the children. You know, they had the little concerts and - some - entertainments. Well
 - on - on St Davids Day now you know - they would always like to go to school to watch we children St David's Day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would they meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, yes. Oh yes, they - my mother used to take interest, she'd like to go down to ask the teach
ers what they thought of us and where we were backward, took a delight in - in our education, always did, showed interest and that's what they used to say - well, how few parents would do that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes, all types. All types. All types in the school, from the poor classes and - and that's where you could tell the behaviour, and the upbringing of the children, and I think that's what the teachers used to notice you see. They
'd know the type of home we came from with your manners and your behaviour in school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did the shopkeepers children go to school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And the minister's children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. Yes, they'd come to the lower - to the - schools.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 If they saw them sharp, yes. If they saw that they were fairly intelligent - they would take trouble with those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh dear, yes. As I was telling you, these places - the rough places, they would come in gangs, and you knew the gang and you - you'd - you'd go miles from them 'cos you were scared stiff of them. And of course they - they thought it was great, they thrive
d on that, you could always tell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were there any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes, if they weren't - if there wasn't much intelligence, it - depended on - on the child if she was fairly intelligent, if there was anything going on - like
 a - a sort of a - a little play or anything like that - they'd watch who the intelligent ones - put them in you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were there any children left out though when you were playing in the yard and all that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, if they'd been naugh
ty - they were kept in from playtime. Oh that was a big crime to be kept in from playtime, that was very big insult. You were kept in the class, you weren't - and perhaps they - they'd put you to do something, lines or something like that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would there be any children that sort of didn't join in anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes, there were some - very very - shy sheepish children, didn't want to play and didn't want to join in, crotchety children. Oh we'd have them mixed then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You went on to another school then didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How old would you be when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
How old would I have been? Came over here when I was - ten, ten, yes, 1909 - 1909, we came over, I was born 1899. Yes, I'd be about - I started the Central school before we moved here you see. Ready - for the move.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 So you weren't long in Eastern school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No, not - no. I can remember a Miss Thomas was - was our last teacher, and - she was a lovely person but oh very severe, but I always got on well wi
th her, she was very keen on - good manners again, she couldn't stand rude children. Very keen on music. On - teaching us hymns, and I tell you I can remember in my class there, in Miss Thomas's class, that was standard two, in the Eastern school, and she
 
was wonderful reciter and she'd have her out to recite - Dick Tollev's daughter we used to call her, Sarah, she was a wonderful elocutionist and her star turn was - was the Women of Mumble Head, and she was very dramatic in the way she'd - she'd - she use
d to go to the eistedfodds and recite, but she was an excellent reciter, that's Joe Davis's sister, she's dead now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What kind of school was Eastern then, would it be boys, girls or mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Separate. We were separate, yes. And Miss Rees - she was M
rs - George Harris after that, lived up here, they were Mayor and Mayoress one year 1 she was the headmistress of the Eastern school at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How long did it take you to get to school there? It was from Park Street then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, a good quarter of an hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who would go with you then to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh we'd go ourselves, a crowd of us then, we children would meet on the way you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Where did you have your midday meal then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 May Merchant was - oh home, come home for our meals, there were never meals in school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did you think of Eastern school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh I enjoyed it for the small - short time I was there, but I loved the Central school. That's where I spent most of my time you see, 'til I went to the secondary school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You were about ten when you went to the Central school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was that a girls school or mixed?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. It started mixed when I went there first, then they built the boys school here, you see, and - then the boys went all there and we - i
t was all girls, that's how Mr Nicholas was the headmaster, and then when it came separate with the boys and girls when this boys school was built, Miss Perkins became the headmisteress and Mr Nicholas went to the boys you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 It only took you minutes to get there did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, a couple of sec - couple of minutes to go across.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Who would go with you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh go on my own, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And had your midday meal in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 In - her, at home, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did you think of the Central?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh I loved it. I loved the Central, remember Miss - Miss Bessy Ware, oh - she was wonderful to read a story. Oh - she - I never heard anybody read a story ever like Bessy Ware. She - she had such a light voice and such a - and an expression, happy expres
sion on her face you know, and she'd read us these - she was an expert. Now Miss Kent - the Kent's - you remember, no - you wouldn't remember. They lived the - the end house up here on Broad Street. And there were - they had two sisters, Miss Ellen Kent a
n
d Miss Emily Kent. Miss Emily Kent, oh she was severe. She wasn't a likable person at all. Terribly severe. I don't think - I ever liked Miss Kent. Although living in the same street, you couldn't get near her. She wouldn't - she wasn't a lovable personal
ity.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When you say she was severe in school what do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh severe with the cane or anything. Oh and severe if you go wrong and - oh, she was terribly severe. You weren't supposed to do anything wrong. Yes, I had the cane with her. Yes, that 
insulted me. I don't know, I hadn't done my sums right or something, she was terrible she was. I don't think I disliked a teacher like Miss Kent. Miss Emily Kent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How did she punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 With the cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 On your hand?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. And it wo
uld come down believe me. And she had a very long hook nose. Not a bit nice - you couldn't get - that's the only teacher I couldn't get near.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life, at the Central?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, they were keen 
on, again, your good behaviour and - and stick with your work. They were very good, Lallah Thomas was my last teacher there, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 It was a girls school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And your parents showed an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You said they had you coached, when would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Before - now I wasn't very good in maths, I was - maths - and the arts I liked, history and geography, English, literature, they were the subjects I liked. Now - I don't think one of us were very bril
liant in - maths. Only Bryn, my younger brother, he was very brilliant in maths, but - none of us were very keen on maths, we preferred the arts and - my mother I remember before the secondary school had been built now and they were to try to scholarships
 with the secondary school - and - she had me - coached - with - Lallah would coach us you see, at the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Your schoolteacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes. Lallah Thomas. Mrs W.R. Thomas after, and she was courting - when we were mixed W.R. was teaching there too yo
u see, in the mixed school, and we were watching points now the - they were courting you see. 'Cos Lallah was from Neith, and W.R. Port Talbot. Well when W.R. went across to the boys then - his classroom was opposite our class room, and you could see now 
y
ou were watching now the moves - of W.R. and Lallah through the windows, and I was the one that used to carry notes for Lallah across to W.R. and then there'd be notes coming back from W.R. to Lallah. I remember always taking these love notes across back 
and forth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would she coach you once a week or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 For how long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 She'd stay - she'd stay for an hour with us, we that wanted coaching. In school. And then go back to Neath.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And your mother paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh yes. Very small fee it was mind, she was - but - my mother would pay, she'd - on the maths it was, that was my weak subject.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were there gangs in the Central?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh dear, yes. Terrible. The celluloid gang, the Goitre gang, and Pennacarr 
mind, some - they were terrors from Pennacarr, they were beyond - and - of course the old Taibach when we were in the Eastern were up the Side, but these were the two that we were frightened of, was the - but particularly the Celluloid, they were noted. T
hey were the hooligans of the place, were terrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did the children come from similar types of home to your own in the Central?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Well not the Celluloid and Pennacarr they were very poor homes you see, very poor. Very dirty homes. You see, they we
re children that you wouldn't mix with, they were - they weren't very sweet smelling to begin with, you know, you could tell that they were - very crude, came from very very - poor - oh I don't know, there was something very very - ignorant about them alt
ogether. Oh it was heathen - it was heathenish, it was heathenish. Beyond.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 It was quite a long way too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
It was. Look miles - it - well sure to be two miles from Goit - from - Celluloid and the Central. And the Pennacarr people, I don't know, they were so rough. So I haven't got much - room - room for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 ennacarr. Chapel, look a lot of us go to chapel, because you know they were - such a lot of hooligans.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would it because they were such little small houses up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 I think so. I think so,
 the type of people they were, all labouring type and that and not trying to rise the above ordinary - were quite satisfied in keeping down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Then you went on to another school from there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, to secondary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And I believe it was a walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. 1912. Yes. Great do the opening. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were you there at the opening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
My parents were there. All the parents were invited. It was, went when it opened. Very great day for the opening. Oh. I can remember my mother was thrilled, yes, m
y mother was thrilled when she came back to see all these teachers now in their cap and gowns of course you see it was such a big thing then, something new in the history of the - of the - this - this part you see. And my brother Bryn, he was in the Count
y school you see, and there was a great now - competi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 ti}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
on between - he'd swank that the county school was better than the secondary of course you see. And their teachers were better than ours, there was great competition, between Bryn and I, he in the count
ry, me at the secondary. But I had a whale of a time there, oh I enjoyed it very much.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 When you first started there what time in the morning did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And came back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Half past twelve. Back at a half past one - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And then finish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And it was a mixed school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Mixed. Mixed school there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You walked because it was only down the bottom of your road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That's right. Very easy to get there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 And you had your midday meal at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did you think of the secondary school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh I loved it. I loved it yes. Mr Tom Lewis was the headmaster. And Miss Brown was - was the - his - history and geography. Miss Edwards - was English and literature. And - she always chose me to - w
hen we were on the Shakespearean readings, plays - my star turn was Portia in the Merchant of Venice. I was always chosen of that for the reading of Portia. Oh I - I enjoyed the secondary school very much. And Miss - Miss Kitty - Kitty Daniel was the Wels
h
 teacher, and - at then - but they tell me she was quite different after my time. Oh - she had no control on the class and the boys would start, you know, with the lockers. She - the lockers would go up and down as soon as - you know - then we wouldn't ch
a
nge classrooms, the teachers would change for the different subjects you see. And - but - oh Miss Brown, we were scared of her. Oh - she was very severe. Oh dear yes. She could command a - she could command the class. But I don't know what it was about Mi
s
s - Miss Daniel, but as soon as she'd enter well and she - she'd show that she - she was chickenhearted, I don't know what it was, but the locker - the covers of the lockers were going up and down, pandemonium let loose. And she'd have to call Mr Lewis in
 to to control the class and she'd start her lesson. I think she showed fright you see, she was very shy - but they tell me she was quite the opposite after I left. They were all scared stiff of her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life in the secondary school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
I always found that, I always found that - there - in that time different to now, that they were very keen - on - good behaviour, good manners and respect. That was a big thing in the - in my - my time. And I thin
k it's a pity that - there isn't more of that today you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about the way you were speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh we had to be careful how we spoke. How we behaved.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - oh dear me yes. Yes, I wouldn't be late for the world. And it was a very fine - well they kept wonderful discipline there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh stay in - stay in for lines, but fortunately I - I never experienced that. 'Cos there was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How did they punish the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh had to go to Mr - Mr - Mr Lewis the headmaster, the teachers I don't remember they ever punished us. 'Cos -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would the girls be treated the same as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, they'd give - oh give them lines more, the boys would hav
e - would have to go to the headmaster for the caning. But he wasn't very severe mind, nobody was really frightened of Mr Tom Lewis. And I tell you he was a scream. If one of the teachers missing ill or something he'd come - he would sit in the lesson, he
'
d give us something, but - spin yarns. I can see him now, and he'd sit - he'd say the most ridiculous yarns you ever heard in your life. Oh no substance you know Mr. Lewis. We did - we didn't him very much as a - as a very scholarly man, you know. We were
n't afraid of him at all. No, he was - he was a scream. But it was Mr Ben Davis took us in music, he was - he was a bit severe but a lovely musician. And he was in science too. Used to go to him in the lab.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What did the children have to do there to be punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh if they - if they were - were rude or were - very fond of sho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 o}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 ting paper at one or the other, perhaps - perhaps put notes in your desk. Boys would put notes in a girls desk and I know one boy, he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 had a crush on me, Ian Griffith}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 . Oh - I 
was scared stiff of him, but he would run after me everywhere, and he was very - he was sitting next to me you see and he put notes in the desk, and the teacher was catching him putting these notes you know, these love notes in the desk. And of course he 
w
as kept in you see, kept in oh 'til five o'clock. But he was a daredevil of a - of a boy you know. Lovable boy but - I was very frightened that he'd run after me everywhere. He was the daredevil of the class, our form. Ivan Hanson and Gomer Rees and them 
w
ere in my form you see, and there was a girl there, she was brilliant in maths, and her names was - Millie Whatley, and of course I was good in the arts you see, and we used to compete every - every form, one would come top one - one - one year - one - on
e
 form - one one term, and the other the other, she beat me in maths of course and I'd beat her in the - in the English, and Ivor Hanson and Gomer Rees were the two that were competing with each other. And we were two couples that were competing in the - i
n the class you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh dear yes, a great interest. But of course - I was going in for teaching. But - oh and - the schoolmaster Mr Tom Lewis never forgave my parents or me for go - for 
leaving you know. Because my - they opened this business for my brother you see, the - the year before the war, 1913, and of course I was taken from the school then to - to be with him in the business you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 You were only fourteen really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Only
 fourteen then. But I did enjoy to. The time I was there mind. Mm. I'd love to have stayed on. And I feel I often - sorry that my career there came to an end because I - I loved it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh yes, you could see - this Millie Whatley now that was a - could see she was from a very poor family, but very brainy. There were the different types. Lots of Catholic children going - coming to the school too at that time, yes. And they were a very
 nice girl - very nice girls, they were - they - you couldn't say there was - anybody very poor there, not in the Central. They were all the better - type.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How about the Secondary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 At second - the sec. Oh no, you wouldn't say there was anybody very poor, but if there was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you all have to try the scholarship to get in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were there any paying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No. Nobody allowed to pay, you had to try the scholarship there, no payment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes, if they saw there was something - that you were bright in certain subjects they would, they would take great trouble with you. Call you out to explain to the class and that sort of thing you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were there any gangs or groups in that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
I can't remember gangs there. No. No, they were a different type of people, they were a nicer class people who went there. 'Cos they were a people now then - that wanted their children again to get on you see, the people -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Were there any children who were left out of things in the Sec?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes - there were some very stupid - and you could see the teachers couldn't be bothered very much with them, you know, yes, stupid - some - very backward.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 In the Secondary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Yes - you'd be surprised. They weren't trying I don't think. Because you see - they didn't have to pay as you know they passed in - I don't know how they passed in some of them at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 They'd just opened -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Fourteen was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That's right, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 1913 you said you left?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was it? '13. Yes, must have been that. Or '12. Yes. Oh yes, must have been 13 because my -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 1913 so that would make you about fourteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That's right. I left school, that's it, about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Would you have stayed longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you have any part time education afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, I used to go to night schools. Yes. On the County sch
ool I'd go to night school, I'd take English - and - oh - didn't take Welsh of course, didn't allow that, and I was very fond - I joined - an art class, and fancywork class, that sort of thing. And of course then we - we joined - we were in the different 
choirs and - I joined a drama group you see, joined a drama group and the operatic - no, the operatic came after that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 I would like to have carried on. I would like to have carried on. I always f
eel that - it would have - I would have enjoyed a career - a teaching career, I would have been in my oil with - with - teach - children I think, I'm very fond of children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How did you feel at the time when you had to leave?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 I felt very - very u
pset to tell you the truth, yes. And - my parents thought I - I'd do well in - in the - in the business with Idris and do the helping to build his business up, because I could speak Welsh or English and so many people would come down from the v}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 lleys to bu
y you see, and you'd be surprised how keen they were, on the Welsh. Now - when my sister joined us - when she left the - insurance office and joined us in the business - she couldn't speak Welsh you see, and they'd all ask for me - the - your sister speak
s Welsh, could - should she serve us. I was very popular in the shop, and I - I quite enjoyed it mind, because it's very interesting with business people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Do y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 ou think you benefi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 ted from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh yes. Oh it was a great help. Oh yes, I
 loved school because - you know, the things I learnt then - and that's why I think it's good to train your mind when you are young because the things you learn when you are young are the things that remain with you in your - older years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 While you were at school did you have a part time job or any means of earning a little regular money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No. Oh no, no, no. No. We helped at home. Helped our parents. In the house you know, did any work that we could to - to do any little jobs to - help my mother 
with the work in the house because with four - four - boys you know there was a lot of work - where - with them. No, no, we - we were prepared - very occupied, and she - always liked us to have - hobbies, and there was so much music in the house with my b
rothers and that you see and - that - it was all - a very very - active house, and - we never did anything outside - outside in - in jobs I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Your first full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was in the shop. In with my brother, in business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 How did you get it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Yes, easily, got it through the parents opening the business for my brother. Oh I - I thoroughly enjoyed that mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What exactly did you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - serving - customers of course, it was in a - a fancy - outfitter shop - my brother o
f course did the measuring of the suits and all that, but I did most of the serving, helped to dress the windows. My brother was very artistical and doing - he won prizes - for his window dressing, and I used to - help him with the windows. Plenty to do, 
look after the stocks and I'd - go to Cardiff to the warehouses to buy for him you know, we'd go together on Thursdays - Thursday afternoons. With the trap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 That was mens outfitting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Mens outfitting. Very interesting, I - I enjoyed it very much, there were such nice people coming in too you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - very long hours then. I can remember coming home - through Station Road on a Christmas Eve at half past eleven. Very late hours.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What time did you start in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Oh nine o'clock. And then - I'd come home at twelve to my lunch then go back home by one, I had a bicycle then to cycle up and down, yes, and my brother would come home then at one you see and he - he'd have his lunch, come back until he g
ot married of course, then they lived on the premises, but - I quite - I quite enjoyed the - the business.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What was the finishing time in the afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh - well we wouldn't close in the week 'til eight o'clock, in the week nights, but Saturda
y nights ten, to half past. And then of course on the holiday. I tell you Christmas and - any holidays, at Christmas time it was always half past eleven, by the time you see - you'd closed, people - the same ones would come - the late comers all the time,
 
they knew - you knew the late comers, well of course it was so busy that the counters were stacked with tie boxes and - and handkerchief boxes, all sorts of things, shirt box - anything you'd been serving, well all that had to be cleared up before you lef
t the shop of course you see. And then we'd be walking down home - wa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6976895\charrsid2636949 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 ked to the wide, you see, when we'd come back home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What about Sunday, did you work on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Oh no. No, no work on Sunday. It was - our church on Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Half day, did you have a half day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
Thursday, half day. Oh yes, we'd have a - a lovely day that day. I can remember my brother when he was a - Idris, when he was in Osborn Harris's as a - as an assistant - before they opened the business for him and - the boys then 
- the assistants, the young boys, they'd - every shop had a - had a bike, and it had the advert of the shop and it was - and you know the crossbar would be - Osborn Harris, Outfitter, and different boys from different shops would meet in Baglen, and - the
y decided this - this Thursday afternoon they'd all meet at Era, go cycling. And - there was one fellow, he was an awful lad, Bryn Jarrett, and they decided they would come down Baglen Hill, Pentila Hill you know, turn round Wyburn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6257333\charrsid2636949 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 s corner, remember that, into the s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6257333\charrsid2636949 q}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 uare, without brakes. Well of course they all had brakes but this Bryn Jarrett. Well - he came down, of course he couldn't stop, he had to turn round Wyburn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6257333\charrsid2636949 
\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 s corner, went into the square and there was a man at the bottom - there was no - there 
was no - glass to the front they were wide open, he was sitting at the back - the bottom of the stair nursing a baby, and - he went in, bike and all into the passage, into the man nursing the baby on the stair. I always think of that you know when my brot
hers said he was - he - it was very very jolly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you have holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 No, not in those days. No. And it was very poor pay to start.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 What were you paid, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Half a crown. To start - a week. So that they could build up a business.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you feel this was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No indeed I didn't. Now I feel when I could have had a teaching career - what I threw up you know, but still - I helped my brother and I was satisfied, it was a nice little business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 
No, she kept us. It was my mother and father kept up. I - it was a pound I earned when I left - when I got married. I was earning - pound I was earning then. That's the most I ever had - in those days. No ind
eed I'm sorry to say there was nothing given to the parents but - they were keeping us because I mean we could never - we could never have kept ourselves in the way we were kept. We were dressed nicely always, and - allowed to go to so many functions and 
-
 join so many different things you see. But - they - oh no, the parents really - we were an expense. My parents never gained on one of us. We were really - kept by them more than - well until they got on their feet and married and had a good wage themselv
es you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5506367 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 Was it only your brother, was there any other person working in the shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7226846 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13726020\charrsid2636949 My brother and I - and my younger sister came later on. Blod.
